layer|23|Jug Girard|HB}}\n{{NFLplayer|33|Ollie Cline|FB}}\n{{NFLplayer|34|Pat Harder|FB}}\n{{NFLplayer|37|Doak Walker|HB}}\n{{NFLplayer|45|Byron Bailey|HB}}\n\n|Wide Receivers=\n{{NFLplayer|80|Cloyce Box|E}}\n{{NFLplayer|81|Bill Swiacki|E}}\n{{NFLplayer|82|Leon Hart|E}}\n\n|Tight Ends=\n\n|Offensive Linemen=\n{{NFLplayer|51|Vince Banonis|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|62|Jim Martin|d=American football|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|63|Dick Stanfel|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|70|Gus Cifelli|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|76|Lou Creekmur|G}}\n\n|Defensive Linemen=\n{{NFLplayer|65|Les Bingaman|MG}}\n{{NFLplayer|73|Thurman McGraw||DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|75|John Prchlik|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|83|Jim Doran|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|85|Sonny Gandee|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|86|Blaine Earon|DE}}\n\n|Linebackers=\n{{NFLplayer|53|LaVern Torgeson|LB}}\n{{NFLplayer|60|Dick Flanagan|LB}}\n\n|Defensive Backs=\n{{NFLplayer|24|Jack Christiansen|S}}\n{{NFLplayer|25|Jim David|d=American football|DH}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Yale Lary|DH}}\n{{NFLplayer|44|Don Doll|S}}\n\n|Special Teams=\n{{NFLplayer|34|Pat Harder|K}}\n{{NFLplayer|36|Bob Smith|d=defensive back, born 1925|P}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Yale Lary|PR}}\n{{NFLplayer|24|Jack Christiansen|KR}}\n{{NFLplayer|84|Pat Summerall|K}}\n\n|Reserve Lists=\n\n|Practice Squad=\n\n}}\n\n==Season summary==\n\n===Preseason===\nThe [[1951 Detroit Lions season|1951 Lions]] had compiled a 7\u20134\u20131 record and finished in a tie for second place in the NFL National Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=1951 Detroit Lions|publisher=Sport Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 5, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/1951_roster.htm}}</ref>  The 1952 team was a veteran group, including quarterback [[Bobby Layne]] (fifth year in NFL, third in Detroit), fullback [[Pat Harder]] (seventh year in NFL, second in Detroit), halfbacks [[Doak Walker]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit) and [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] (seventh year in NFL, third in Detroit), ends [[Cloyce Box]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit) and [[Leon Hart]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit), defensive linemen [[Les Bingaman]] (fifth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[John Prchlik]] (fourth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[Thurman \"Fum\" McGraw]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit), and defensive backs [[Don Doll]] (fourth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[Jack Christiansen]] (second year in NFL, both in Detroit), and [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] (fifth year in pro ball, fourth in Detroit).\n\nThe Lions won all six pre-season exhibition games as follows: (1) 28\u201313 over the [[1952 Chicago Cardinals season|Chicago Cardinals]] on August 18 at [[Amarillo, Texas]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Box Scores 2 Touchdowns, as Lions Whip Cards, 28-13|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 19, 1952|page=17|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223806/box_scores_2_tds/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (2) 7\u20133 over [[1952 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] at [[Little Rock, Arkansas]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne-Doak Toss Enough as Lions Top Eagles, 7-3|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 24, 1952|page=29|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223889/layne_doak_toss_enough/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (3) 33\u201313 over the [[1952 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] on September 2;<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions' 2nd-Half Rally Outclasses Giants, 33\u201313|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 3, 1952|page=21|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223591/lions_2nd_half_rally_outclasses_giants/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (4) 28\u201321 over the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] on September 6;<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Rally, Defeat Cleveland, 28-21, on Aerials|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 7, 1952|page=21|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223763/lions_rally_defeat_cleveland/}}</ref> (5) 21\u201314 over the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]] on September 12 at Dallas;<ref>{{cite news|title=Walker Rallies Lions for 21-14 Victory Over Dallas|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 13, 1952|page=13|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223947/walker_rallies_lions/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> and (6) 45\u20137 over the [[1952 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] on September 20.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unbeaten Lions Overstaffed: Parker's Worries Happy Ones|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 22, 1952|page=27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223728/unbeaten_lions_overstaffed/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> The Lions were considered a favorite for the NFL championship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Time to Tell: Can Lions Claim Gridiron Greatness?|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 15, 1952|page=26|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223522/can_lions_claim_gridiron_greatness/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Taste Glory After 17-Year Fast|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 29, 1952|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223135/lions_taste_glory/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Week 1: at San Francisco===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Detroit\n|V1=0 |V2=3 |V3=0 |V4=0\n|Host='''San Francisco'''\n|H1= 7|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=3\n|Date=September 28\n|Location=[[Kezar Stadium]], San Francisco\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=52,750\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn September 28, 1952, the Lions lost the first game of the regular season to the [[San Francisco 49ers]] by a 17\u20133 score in heavy fog at [[Kezar Stadium]] in San Francisco. The loss was the fourth in a row for the Lions against the 49ers, dating back to the [[1950 Detroit Lions season|1950 season]]. The Lions' offense was limited to a 21-yard field goal by [[Doak Walker]] in the second quarter.  Detroit turned the ball over five times on three interceptions and two fumbles. [[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]] rushed 19 times for 80 yards and scored the 49ers first touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|title=Just Like '51: Lions Fall to 49ers, 17-3: Flub '52 Opener in Frisco Fog; Fumbles Help Detroit Downfall|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|page=25|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225506/just_like_51/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 3 at San Francisco 49ers 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195209280sfo.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 2: at Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=0 |V2=14 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host=Los Angeles\n|H1=0|H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 3\n|Location=[[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=42,743\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Friday, October 3, 1952, the Lions defeated the defending NFL champion [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], 17\u201314, at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. [[Bobby Layne]] threw two touchdown passes to [[Cloyce Box]], the first set up by a [[Les Bingaman]] interception. The Lions led, 14\u20130, but the Rams scored later in the second quarter on a 20-yard run. [[Doak Walker]] kicked a 13-yard field goal in the third quarter that ended up providing the deciding margin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne Hits Box With 2 TD Passes: Lions Lead Rams in Final Period, 17-14|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=13, 14|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225856/lions_lead_rams_in_final_period/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 17 at Los Angeles Rams 14|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210030ram.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 3: San Francisco===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''San Francisco'''\n|V1=0 |V2=14 |V3=7 |V4=7\n|Host=Detroit\n|H1=0|H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=0\n|Date=October 12\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=56,822\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 12, 1952, the Lions lost, 28-0 for the fifth consecutive time to the San Francisco 49ers.  The Lions did not convert a first down in the first half, totaled only 114 yards of offense in the game, and were shut out for the first time since October 1948.  The game was played at Briggs Stadium in front of the largest home crowd (56,822) in Lions history to that point. Bob Latshaw in the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' called it \"as inept an exhibition as has ever been seen in Briggs Stadium\", as the 49ers \"smother[ed] any semblance of a Detroit offense.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions At Worst for Best Crowd in Detroit History: 56,822 See 49ers Stage 28-0 Rout; Home Forces Held to 4 First Downs|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 13, 1952|pages=25, 27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226085/lions_at_worst_for_best_crowd_in/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=San Francisco 49ers 28 at Detroit Lions 0|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210120det.htm}}</ref>  Having been billed as a championship contender in the preseason, the Lions had a 1-2 record after three regular season games.\n\n===Week 4: Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Los Angeles\n|V1=6 |V2=7 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=0|H2=7 |H3=14 |H4=3\n|Date=October 19\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=40,152\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 19, 1952, the Lions defeated the Los Angeles Rams, 24-16, in front of a crowd of 40,152 at Briggs Stadium. After the Lions' poor performance the prior week against the 49ers, the Detroit crowd booed the Lions as they came onto the field. The boos continued as the Rams took a 13-0 lead in the second quarter.  From that point forward, the Lions outscored the Rams, 24 to 3. The comeback began with a 64-yard touchdown pass from [[Bobby Layne]] to [[Cloyce Box]].  The Lions scored two more touchdowns in the third quarter on a 29-yard interception return by [[LaVern Torgeson]] and a 10-yard touchdown pass from [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] to Cloyce Box. [[Pat Harder]] added a field goal in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Spot Rams 13-0 Lead, Roar to 24-16 Victory: Turn Jeers of 40,152 to Cheers; Box Scores 2 TDs as Harder Lifts Club|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 20, 1952|page=33|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226210/lions_spot_rams_130_lead_roar_to/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Rams 16 at Detroit Lions 24|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210190det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 5: at Green Bay===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=14 |V2=14 |V3=14 |V4=10\n|Host=Green Bay\n|H1= 7|H2=3 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 26\n|Location=[[City Stadium (Green Bay)|City Stadium]], [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=24,656\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 26, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], 52\u201317, before a crowd of 24,656 at [[City Stadium (Green Bay)|City Stadium]] in Green Bay. The 52 points scored by the Lions tied the franchise's all-time, single-game scoring record. [[Bobby Layne]] threw three touchdown passes, and [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] rushed for two touchdowns. [[Jug Girard]] caught two touchdown passes and gained 130 yards, 69 receiving and 61 rushing.  The Lions also scored on a 46-yard interception return by [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] and a 65-yard punt return by [[Jack Christiansen]].  The defense held the Packers to 53 rushing yards, recovered four fumbles, and intercepted five passes. [[Pat Harder]] scored nine points on a 16-yard field goal and six extra points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Packers Just What Doctor Ordered for Lions, 52 to 17: Layne Goes by Air for 3 Touchdowns; Defensive Unit Has Hand in 4 Scores|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=33, 35|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225044/packers_just_what_doctor_ordered_for/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 52 at Green Bay Packers 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210260gnb.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 6: Cleveland===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cleveland\n|V1=3 |V2=0 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=0|H2=10 |H3=0 |H4=7\n|Date=November 2\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=56,029\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 2, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], 17-6, in front of a crowd of 56,029 at Briggs Stadium.  The game was the first meeting between the Lions and the Browns, the latter having joined the NFL in 1950.  On defense, the Lions forced four turnovers, including three interceptions, and held the Browns to two [[Lou Groza]] field goals.  On offense, [[Bobby Layne]] threw two touchdown passes to [[Leon Hart]]. Hart, playing on his 24th birthday, caught eight passes for 109 yards.  [[Pat Harder]] also kicked a 43-yard field goal. Defensive end [[Jim Doran]] at one point sacked Cleveland quarterback [[Otto Graham]] on consecutive plays for losses totaling 36 yards.  The Lions intercepted three passes and held the Browns to 12 rushing yards in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|title=56,029 See Leon Tally 2: Lions Beat Browns, 17-6, with Layne-Hart Punch|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 3, 1952|pages=33, 35|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226355/lions_beat_browns_176/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland Browns 6 at Detroit Lions 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211020det.htm}}</ref><ref name=haslubr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YmNQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fw8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4556%2C2617521 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Hart ace as Lions upset Browns, 17-6 |date=November 3, 1952 |page=4, part 2 }}</ref>\n\n===Week 7: at Pittsburgh===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=3 |V2=7 |V3=7 |V4=14\n|Host=Pittsburgh\n|H1=0|H2=0 |H3=6 |H4=0\n|Date=November 9\n|Location=[[Forbes Field]], [[Pittsburgh]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=26,170\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 9, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], 31\u20136, before a crowd of 26,170 at [[Forbes Field]] in Pittsburgh. Usually a pass-oriented offense, the Lions adopted a different approach against the Steelers, rushing for a season-high 321 yards. [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] rushed for 107 yards on 20 carries, and [[Jug Girard]] contributed 71 yards and two touchdowns on six carries. [[Bobby Layne]] completed only four of 17 passes  for 70 yards, 46 of which came on a touchdown pass to [[Cloyce Box]] in the third quarter.  On defense, the Lions held the Steelers to minus three yards rushing and intercepted two passes.  Defensive halfback [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] recovered a fumbled lateral that set up a field goal in the first quarter and returned an interception 90 yards late in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Win, Tie 49ers for Lead: Pittsburgh Ground to Bits, 31-6; Hunchy, Girard Pace Vicious Rushing Race|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 10, 1952|pages=33, 34|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226768/pittsburgh_ground_to_bits_316/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 31 at Pittsburgh Steelers 6|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211090pit.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 8: Dallas===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Dallas\n|V1=0 |V2=0 |V3=13 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=10 |H2=19 |H3=0 |H4=14\n|Date=November 16\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=33,304\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 16, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]], 43\u201313, before a crowd of 33,304 at Briggs Stadium. The loss was the eighth straight for the Texans.  In the first half, the Lions took a 29-0 lead on two [[Pat Harder]] field goals, a 58-yard punt return by [[Yale Lary]], an eight-yard run by [[Bobby Layne]], a 55-yard touchdown pass from Layne to [[Cloyce Box]], and a safety when defensive end [[Sonny Gandee]] tackled Pittsburgh quarterback [[Frank Tripucka]] in the end zone. In the fourth quarter, Harder kicked his third field goal, and fullback [[Ollie Cline]] scored on a two-yard run.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Hand Dallas 8th Loss, 43-13: Stay Tied with 49ers for League Lead|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|page=33|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226836/lions_hand_dallas_8th_loss/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dallas Texans 13 at Detroit Lions 43|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211160det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 9: at Chicago===\n\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Detroit\n|V1=3 |V2=13 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host='''Chicago'''\n|H1=10|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=7\n|Date=November 23\n|Location=[[Wrigley Field]], [[Chicago]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=37,508\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 23, 1952, the Lions lost to the [[1952 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], 24\u201323, before a crowd of 37,508 at [[Wrigley Field]] in [[Chicago]]. [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] scored two rushing touchdowns, and [[Pat Harder]] also kicked a 31-yard field goal for the Lions.  The Lions led, 16\u201310, at halftime, but the Bears took the lead in the third quarter on a 59-yard touchdown pass from [[George Blanda]] to [[Billy Stone (American football)|Billy Stone]].  The Lions retook the lead, 23\u201317, when [[Jack Christiansen]] returned a punt 79 yards for a touchdown in the fourth quarter.  With nine seconds left in the game, Blanda threw a two-yard touchdown pass to [[Ed Sprinkle]] for the winning score.<ref>{{cite news|title=9 Seconds Left \u2013 Bears Shade Lions, 24 to 23: Long Drive Offsets 79-Yard TD Run by Christiansen|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 24, 1952|page=32|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226932/bears_shade_lions/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 23 at Chicago Bears 24|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211230chi.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 10: Green Bay===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Green Bay\n|V1=3 |V2=14 |V3=7 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 3|H2=21 |H3=7 |H4=17\n|Date=November 27\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=39,101\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Thanksgiving Day, November 27, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], 48\u201324, before a crowd of 39,101 at Briggs Stadium. The Lions scored 100 points in two games against the Packers during the 1952 season. In the Thanksgiving game, the Lions scored on five touchdown passes \u2013 three thrown by [[Bobby Layne]] and three caught by [[Cloyce Box]]. Layne accounted for over 300 yards of total offense \u2013 63 yards on 13 rushing carries and 249 yards on 16 of 30 passing. Box caught a total of nine passes for 155 yards. [[Pat Harder]] scored 17 points on a touchdown run, two field goals, and five extra points.  On defense, the Lions forced eight turnovers, including six fumble recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=On Turkey Day, Lions Cook Packers' Goose, 48-24: 39,101 See Detroit Get 1st Place|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=43, 46|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225360/on_turkey_day_lions_cook_packers_goose/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Green Bay Packers 24 at Detroit Lions 48|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211270det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 11: Chicago===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Chicago\n|V1=7 |V2=7 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 14|H2=7 |H3=10 |H4=14\n|Date=December 7\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=50,410\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 7, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], 45\u201321, before a crowd of 50,410 at [[Briggs Stadium]]. The game was the Lions' first victory over the Bears in Detroit since 1945. [[Bobby Layne]] and [[Cloyce Box]] connected for three touchdown passes in the first half: for 29 and 28 yards in the first quarter and for 25 yards in the second quarter. Layne also threw an 11-yard pass to [[Jim Doran]] in the third quarter. In all, Layne completed 22 of 35 passes for 296 yards. Detroit's defense held the Bears to 37 rushing yards and 171 passing yards and intercepted six Chicago passes.  Defensive back [[Jack Christiansen]] also played at running back, rushing for 54 yards and a touchdown on six carries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Brush Bears Aside, 45-21: Layne Hits Box for 3 Touchdows|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 8, 1952|page=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4224039/lions_brush_bears_aside/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago Bears 21 at Detroit Lions 45|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212070det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 12: Dallas===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Dallas\n|V1=0 |V2=0 |V3=0 |V4=6\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 0|H2=14 |H3=10 |H4=17\n|Date=December 13\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=12,252\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Saturday, December 13, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]], 41\u20136, before a small crowd of 12,252 at [[Briggs Stadium]].  With the win and the Rams' victory the following day, the Lions and Rams became co-champions of the NFL's National Conference. The game had originally been scheduled for December 14 in Dallas, but the NFL assumed control of the Texans one month earlier, and NFL commissioner [[Bert Bell]] decided that the Texans would play their remaining games \"on the road.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bmNQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fw8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2159%2C5094346 |newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|Milwaukee Sentinel]] |agency=Associated Press |title=NFL takes over Dallas Texans |date=November 15, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/11/15/archives/national-football-league-takes-franchise-back-from-dallas-club.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |agency=Associated Press |title=National Football League takes franchise back from Dallas club |date=November 14, 1952 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Bobby Layne]] led the Lions to a 14\u20130 lead in the first half on touchdown passes of 18 yards (a [[Flea flicker (American football)|flea flicker]] with Layne passing to [[Cloyce Box]] who immediately lateraled the ball to [[Pat Harder]]) and 77 yards to [[Cloyce Box]]. Layne was injured (strained knee ligament) shortly before halftime and did not return to the game. [[Jim Hardy]] took over at quarterback and led the Lions to 27 points in the second half, including two touchdown passes to Box of 40 and 41 yards.  [[Jack Christiansen]] also ran 65 yards for a touchdown in the fourth quarter, the Lions' longest rushing play of the season.  Layne completed 10 of 20 passes for 167 yards, and Hardy completed nine of 15 passes for 147 yards.  Box caught a total of seven passes for 202 yards and three touchdowns, setting a new Lions' team record with 15 touchdown receptions in a season.  Harder scored 17 points in the game on a touchdown, two field goals, and five extra points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne Hurt, but Lions Win Share of Title: 41\u20136 Rout Completed by Hardy; Bobby's Knee Hurt; Box Sets TD Mark|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 14, 1952|page=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4222734/layne_hurt_but_lions_win/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dallas Texans 6 at Detroit Lions 41|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212130det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Playoff game \u2013 Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Los Angeles\n|V1=0 |V2=7 |V3=0 |V4=14\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 7|H2=7 |H3=10 |H4=7\n|Date=December 21\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=47,645\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 21, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], 31\u201321, in a playoff game to decide who would advance to the NFL Championship Game.  The Lions had beaten the Rams twice in the regular season and were a 1\u00bd-point favorite in the playoff.<ref name=flirdu>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sCkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tA8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3716%2C6056106 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Favor Lions by 1\u00bd points in Ram duel |date=December 21, 1952 |page=3B }}</ref>  The playoff game was played in heavy fog and rain at [[Briggs Stadium]] before a crowd of 47,645. [[Pat Harder]] led both teams with 72 rushing yards on eight carries and scored 19 points on two touchdown runs in the first half, a 43-yard field goal in the third quarter, and four extra points.  The Rams double-teamed and sometimes triple-teamed [[Cloyce Box]], which opened the running game and allowed [[Leon Hart]] to have one of his best receiving days. Hart scored in the third quarter on a 24-yard pass from [[Doak Walker]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Beat Rams, 31\u201321, to Gain NFL Title Playoff: 'Old Pros' Make Good in Clutch; Harder Scores 19; Late LA Rally Halted|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 22, 1952|pages=33, 34|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4222879/lions_beat_rams/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Rams 21 at Detroit Lions 31|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212210det.htm}}</ref><ref name=hchup19>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2EUxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7240%2C91924 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Harder chalks up 19 points in Lions' 31-21 playoff triumph over Rams |date=December 22, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref name=hlltworms>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hHxIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4WoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4695%2C6214058 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |agency=Associated Press |title=Harder leads Lions to 31-21 win over Rams |date=December 22, 1952 |page=22}}</ref>\n\n===NFL Championship Game===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=0 |V2=7 |V3=7 |V4=3\n|Host=Cleveland\n|H1= 0|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=December 28\n|Location=[[Cleveland Stadium|Memorial Stadium]], [[Cleveland]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=50,934\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 28, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], 17\u20137, in the [[1952 NFL Championship Game]] at [[Cleveland Stadium|Memorial Stadium]] in [[Cleveland]]. The Lions had defeated the Browns in both a preseason game and in a regular season game and were favored by 3\u00bd points.<ref name=lhaft>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3kUxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1843%2C1153999 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Lions, hot after 1st title, favored by 3\u00bd points |date=December 28, 1952 |page=1B }}</ref>\n\n[[Bobby Layne]] rushed for a touchdown in the second quarter, and the Lions led, 7\u20130, at halftime. In the third quarter, [[Doak Walker]] ran 67 yards for a touchdown to extend the Lions' lead to 14 points. Walker's touchdown in the championship game was his first of the 1952 season.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote: \"The Doaker was the Walker of old as he twisted and turned, eluded tackler after tackler and ran 67 yards for the Lions' second touchdown.\"<ref name=DFPC/>  The Browns narrowed the lead to 14\u20137 on a seven-yard touchdown run by [[Chick Jagade]] in the third quarter. [[Pat Harder]] added a 36-yard field goal in the fourth quarter. The Browns' outgained the Lions 384 yards to 258 and had 22 first downs to 10 for Detroit.  The Lions' defense mounted four goal-line stands against the Browns' offense led by [[Otto Graham]], and [[Lou Groza]] missed three field goal attempts.<ref name=DFPC>{{cite news|title=Lions Beat Browns, 17\u20137, Win NFL Title: 50,934 See Defense Turn Tide: Detroit Rides Two Mistakes To Victory|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 29, 1952|pages=19, 20|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223368/lions_beat_browns/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 17 at Cleveland Browns 7|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212280cle.htm}}</ref><ref name=ltrpbr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=30UxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7077%2C1944826 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Lions trip Browns, 17-7, for NFL crown |date=December 29, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref name=ldfppgjsl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4UUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kGoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6140%2C1346058 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |last=Sell |first=Jack |title=Lions defeat Browns for NFL title, 17-7 |date=December 29, 1952 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards, honors and league leaders==\n\n===Team awards===\nAt the end of the regular season, the Lions players selected defensive end [[Jim Doran]] as the team's most valuable player.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Honor End Jim Doran|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 25, 1952|page=13|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4221586/lions_honor_end_jim_doran/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===All-NFL honors===\n\nThe following six Lions players won All-NFL honors from the [[Associated Press]] (AP), [[United Press International]] (UPI) and/or the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'':\n\n* [[Cloyce Box]] (1st team [[Associated Press]] [AP])\n* [[Lou Creekmur]] (1st team AP, [[United Press]] [UP], and ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' [DN])\n* [[Pat Harder]] (2nd team, AP)\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] (1st team DN, 2nd team AP/UP)\n* [[Bobby Layne]] (1st team AP, 2nd team DN)\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] (1st team UP and DN, 2nd team AP)\n\n===Pro Bowl===\nThe following seven Lions players were selected to play in the [[1953 Pro Bowl]]:<ref>{{cite web|title=1952 Pro Bowlers|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/probowl.htm}}</ref>\n* [[Cloyce Box]]\n* [[Lou Creekmur]]\n* [[Don Doll]]\n* [[Pat Harder]]\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]]\n* [[Bobby Layne]]\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]]jk\n\n===NFL leaders===\nSeveral Lions players were also among the NFL leaders in various statistical categories, including the following:<ref>{{cite web|title=1952 NFL Leaders and Leaderboards|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/leaders.htm}}</ref>\n\n* [[Cloyce Box]]\n:: 15 toucjnjnjhhuuhhuhuhuhuhuhdowns p\n(1st)\n:: 15 receiving touchdowns (1st)\n:: 90 points scored (2nd)\n:: 924 receiving yards (4th)\n:: 22.0 yards per reception (4th)\n:: 77.0 receiving yards per game (4th)\n:: 924 yards from scrimmage (6th)\n:: 42 receptions (9th)\n\n* [[Jack Christiansen]]\n:: 21.5 yards per punt return (1st)\n:: 2 punt returns for touchdown (T-1st)\n:: 79-yard punt return (4th)\n:: 731 punt and kick return yards (4th)\n:: 65-yard rush (7th)\n:: 322 punt return yards (5th)\n:: 25.6 yards per kick return (6th)\n:: 409 kick return yards (10th)\n\n* [[Blaine Earon]]\n:: 5 fumbles recovered (T-2nd)\n\n* [[Pat Harder]]\n:: 85 points scored (4th)\n:: 34 extra points made (2nd)\n:: 11 field goals made (T-2nd)\n:: 47.826 field goal percentage (6th)\n\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]]\n:: 457 rushing yards (5th)\n:: 4.3 yards per rushing attempt (5th)\n:: 45.7 rushing yards per game (6th)\n\n* [[Yale Lary]]\n:: 25.3 yards per kick return (T-7th)\n:: 182 punt return yards (8th)\n:: 11.4 yards per punt return (8th)\n:: 53-yard interception return (8th)\n:: 58-yard punt return (9th)\n\n* [[Bobby Layne]]\n:: 2,410 yards total offense (2nd)\n:: 20 passes intercepted (2nd)\n:: 139 passes completed (3rd)\n:: 1,999 passing yards (3rd)\n:: 19 passing touchdowns (3rd)\n:: 166.6 passing yards per game (3rd)\n:: 4.4 yards per rushing attempt (4th)\n:: 48.4 pass completion percentage (7th)\n:: 411 rushing yards (7th)\n\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]]\n:: 44.7 yards per punt (2nd)\n:: 90-yard interception return (2nd)\n:: 9 interceptions (3rd)\n:: 184 interception return yards (3rd)\n:: 2,729 punting yards (6th)\n\n===Pro Football Hall of Fame===\nFive members of the team were later inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame. They are:\n* [[Bobby Layne]] (inducted 1967)\n* [[Jack Christiansen]] (inducted 1970)\n* [[Yale Lary]] (inducted 1979)\n* [[Doak Walker]] (inducted 1986)\n* [[Lou Creekmur]] (inducted 1996)\n* [[Dick Stanfel]] (inducted 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/1952.htm?redir Detroit Lions on Pro Football Reference]\n*[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x26rm0z_1952-nfl-championship-lions-vs-browns_sport Video: 1952 NFL Championship Lions vs Browns]\n\n{{Detroit Lions seasons}} \n{{1952 Detroit Lions}}\n{{Detroit Lions}}\n{{1952 NFL season by team}}\n\n[[Category:1952 National Football League season by team|Detroit Lions]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions seasons]]\n[[Category:National Football League championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1952 in sports in Michigan|Detroit Lions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL season\n| logo =\n| team = Detroit Lions\n| year = 1952\n| record = 9\u20133\n| division_place = 1st [[Eastern and Western Divisions (NFL) 1933-69|NFL National]]\n| coach = [[Buddy Parker]]\n| owner = \n| stadium = [[Briggs Stadium]]\n| playoffs = '''Won [[1952 NFL Championship Game]]''' vs. [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland]] 17\u20137\n| pro_bowlers = {{Collapsible list\n|title = 7\n|[[Cloyce Box]], DE <br>[[Lou Creekmur]], OG <br>[[Don Doll]], S <br>[[Pat Harder]], FB <br>[[Bob Hoernschemeyer]], RB <br>[[Bobby Layne]], QB <br>[[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]], DB\n}}\n| AP All-pros = {{Collapsible list\n|title = 3\n|1= E [[Cloyce Box]]\n|2 = OG [[Lou Creekmur]]\n|3 = QB [[Bobby Layne]]\n}}\n| uniform = \n| shortnavlink = Lions seasons\n}}\nThe '''{{nfly|1952}} [[Detroit Lions]] [[List of Detroit Lions seasons|season]]''' resulted in the Lions winning their second [[National Football League]] (NFL) championship, having won their first championship 17 years earlier in [[1935 Detroit Lions season|1935]].  The team's co-captains were halfback [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] and defensive tackle [[John Prchlik]], and defensive end [[Jim Doran]] was selected as the team's most valuable player.  In their third year under head coach [[Buddy Parker]], the 1952 Lions compiled a 9\u20133 record during the regular season, finished in a tie with the [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] for first place in the NFL's National Conference, defeated the Rams in a tiebreaker game, and defeated the [[1953 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], 17\u20137, in the [[1952 NFL Championship Game]] at [[Cleveland Stadium|Municipal Stadium]] in [[Cleveland]].\n\nThe 1952 Lions outscored opponents 354 to 192 in 12 regular season games and ranked first in the NFL with an average of 29.5 points scored per game. The offense was led by quarterback [[Bobby Layne]] who ranked second in the NFL with 2,410 yards of [[total offense]] \u2013 1,999 passing and 411 rushing. End [[Cloyce Box]] led the NFL with 15 touchdowns, including nine touchdown catches in the final three games of the regular season. For the third consecutive year, [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] was the team's leading rusher with 457 yards and an average of 4.3 yards per carry. [[Jack Christiansen]] led the NFL with an average of 21.5 yards per punt return, returned two punts for touchdowns, and ranked fourth in the NFL with 731 punt and kick return yards.\n\nThe Lions' defense ranked first in the NFL in points allowed, allowing 16 points per game during the regular season. Defensive back [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] ranked among the NFL leaders with a 90-yard interception return (2nd), nine interceptions (3rd), and 184 interception return yards (3rd). Smith was also the team's punter and ranked second in the NFL with an average of 44.7 yards per punt. Six players from the 1952 Lions team, Layne, Christiansen, halfback [[Doak Walker]], defensive back [[Yale Lary]], and offensive linemen [[Lou Creekmur]] and [[Dick Stanfel]], were later inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Opponent\n!Result\n!Score\n!Location\n!attendance\n|-bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"\n|September 28, 1952\n|at [[1952 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]\n|Loss\n|13\u201317\n|[[Kezar Stadium]], San Francisco\n|<center>54,761</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|October 3, 1952<!-- Fri --> \n|at [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]]\n|Win\n|17\u201314\n|[[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|<center>42,743</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"\n|October 12, 1952\n|San Francisco 49ers\n|Loss\n|0\u201328\n|[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|<center>56,822</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|October 19, 1952\n|Los Angeles Rams\n|Win\n|24\u201316\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>40,152</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|October 26, 1952\n|at [[1952 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]\n|Win\n|52\u201317\n|[[City Stadium (Green Bay)|City Stadium]], [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]]\n|<center>24,656</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|November 2, 1952\n|[[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]\n|Win\n|17\u20136\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>56,029</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|November 9, 1952\n|at [[1952 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|Win\n|31\u20136\n|[[Forbes Field]], [[Pittsburgh]]\n|<center>26,170</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|November 16, 1952\n|[[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]]\n|Win\n|43\u201313\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>33,304</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"\n|November 23, 1952\n|at [[1952 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]\n|Loss\n|23\u201324\n|[[Wrigley Field]], [[Chicago]]\n|<center>37,508</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|November 27, 1952<!--(Thur.)-->\n|Green Bay Packers\n|Win\n|48\u201324\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>39,101</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|December 7, 1952\n|Chicago Bears\n|Win\n|45\u201321\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>50,410</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|December 13, 1952<!--(Sat.)-->\n|Dallas Texans\n|Win\n|41\u20136\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>12,252</center>\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|December 21, 1952\n|[[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]]\n|Win\n|31\u201312\n|Briggs Stadium, Detroit\n|<center>47,645</center>\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|December 28, 1952\n|at [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]\n|Win\n|17\u20137\n|[[Cleveland Stadium|Municipal Stadium]], [[Cleveland]]\n|<center>50,934</center>\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n{{1952 NFL National standings}}\n\n==Roster==\n\n{{NFL final roster\n|Year=1953\n|TeamName=Detroit Lions\n|BC1=#005A8B\n|FC1=#FFFFFF\n|BDC1=#B0B7BC\n|Active=\n|Inactive=\n|PS=\n\n|Quarterbacks=\n{{NFLplayer|1|Jim Hardy}}\n{{NFLplayer|19|Tom Dublinski}}\n{{NFLplayer|22|Bobby Layne}}\n\n|Running Backs=\n{{NFLplayer|14|Bob Hoernschemeyer|HB}}\n{{NFLplayer|23|Jug Girard|HB}}\n{{NFLplayer|33|Ollie Cline|FB}}\n{{NFLplayer|34|Pat Harder|FB}}\n{{NFLplayer|37|Doak Walker|HB}}\n{{NFLplayer|45|Byron Bailey|HB}}\n\n|Wide Receivers=\n{{NFLplayer|80|Cloyce Box|E}}\n{{NFLplayer|81|Bill Swiacki|E}}\n{{NFLplayer|82|Leon Hart|E}}\n\n|Tight Ends=\n\n|Offensive Linemen=\n{{NFLplayer|51|Vince Banonis|C}}\n{{NFLplayer|62|Jim Martin|d=American football|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|63|Dick Stanfel|G}}\n{{NFLplayer|70|Gus Cifelli|T}}\n{{NFLplayer|76|Lou Creekmur|G}}\n\n|Defensive Linemen=\n{{NFLplayer|65|Les Bingaman|MG}}\n{{NFLplayer|73|Thurman McGraw||DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|75|John Prchlik|DT}}\n{{NFLplayer|83|Jim Doran|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|85|Sonny Gandee|DE}}\n{{NFLplayer|86|Blaine Earon|DE}}\n\n|Linebackers=\n{{NFLplayer|53|LaVern Torgeson|LB}}\n{{NFLplayer|60|Dick Flanagan|LB}}\n\n|Defensive Backs=\n{{NFLplayer|24|Jack Christiansen|S}}\n{{NFLplayer|25|Jim David|d=American football|DH}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Yale Lary|DH}}\n{{NFLplayer|44|Don Doll|S}}\n\n|Special Teams=\n{{NFLplayer|34|Pat Harder|K}}\n{{NFLplayer|36|Bob Smith|d=defensive back, born 1925|P}}\n{{NFLplayer|28|Yale Lary|PR}}\n{{NFLplayer|24|Jack Christiansen|KR}}\n{{NFLplayer|84|Pat Summerall|K}}\n\n|Reserve Lists=\n\n|Practice Squad=\n\n}}\n\n==Season summary==\n\n===Preseason===\nThe [[1951 Detroit Lions season|1951 Lions]] had compiled a 7\u20134\u20131 record and finished in a tie for second place in the NFL National Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=1951 Detroit Lions|publisher=Sport Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 5, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/1951_roster.htm}}</ref>  The 1952 team was a veteran group, including quarterback [[Bobby Layne]] (fifth year in NFL, third in Detroit), fullback [[Pat Harder]] (seventh year in NFL, second in Detroit), halfbacks [[Doak Walker]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit) and [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] (seventh year in NFL, third in Detroit), ends [[Cloyce Box]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit) and [[Leon Hart]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit), defensive linemen [[Les Bingaman]] (fifth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[John Prchlik]] (fourth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[Thurman \"Fum\" McGraw]] (third year in NFL, all in Detroit), and defensive backs [[Don Doll]] (fourth year in NFL, all in Detroit), [[Jack Christiansen]] (second year in NFL, both in Detroit), and [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] (fifth year in pro ball, fourth in Detroit).\n\nThe Lions won all six pre-season exhibition games as follows: (1) 28\u201313 over the [[1952 Chicago Cardinals season|Chicago Cardinals]] on August 18 at [[Amarillo, Texas]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Box Scores 2 Touchdowns, as Lions Whip Cards, 28-13|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 19, 1952|page=17|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223806/box_scores_2_tds/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (2) 7\u20133 over [[1952 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] at [[Little Rock, Arkansas]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne-Doak Toss Enough as Lions Top Eagles, 7-3|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=August 24, 1952|page=29|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223889/layne_doak_toss_enough/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (3) 33\u201313 over the [[1952 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] on September 2;<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions' 2nd-Half Rally Outclasses Giants, 33\u201313|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 3, 1952|page=21|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223591/lions_2nd_half_rally_outclasses_giants/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> (4) 28\u201321 over the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] on September 6;<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Rally, Defeat Cleveland, 28-21, on Aerials|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 7, 1952|page=21|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223763/lions_rally_defeat_cleveland/}}</ref> (5) 21\u201314 over the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]] on September 12 at Dallas;<ref>{{cite news|title=Walker Rallies Lions for 21-14 Victory Over Dallas|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 13, 1952|page=13|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223947/walker_rallies_lions/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> and (6) 45\u20137 over the [[1952 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] on September 20.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unbeaten Lions Overstaffed: Parker's Worries Happy Ones|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 22, 1952|page=27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223728/unbeaten_lions_overstaffed/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> The Lions were considered a favorite for the NFL championship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Time to Tell: Can Lions Claim Gridiron Greatness?|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=September 15, 1952|page=26|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223522/can_lions_claim_gridiron_greatness/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Taste Glory After 17-Year Fast|author=Lyall Smith|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 29, 1952|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223135/lions_taste_glory/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Week 1: at San Francisco===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Detroit\n|V1=0 |V2=3 |V3=0 |V4=0\n|Host='''San Francisco'''\n|H1= 7|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=3\n|Date=September 28\n|Location=[[Kezar Stadium]], San Francisco\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=52,750\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn September 28, 1952, the Lions lost the first game of the regular season to the [[San Francisco 49ers]] by a 17\u20133 score in heavy fog at [[Kezar Stadium]] in San Francisco. The loss was the fourth in a row for the Lions against the 49ers, dating back to the [[1950 Detroit Lions season|1950 season]]. The Lions' offense was limited to a 21-yard field goal by [[Doak Walker]] in the second quarter.  Detroit turned the ball over five times on three interceptions and two fumbles. [[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]] rushed 19 times for 80 yards and scored the 49ers first touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|title=Just Like '51: Lions Fall to 49ers, 17-3: Flub '52 Opener in Frisco Fog; Fumbles Help Detroit Downfall|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|page=25|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225506/just_like_51/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 3 at San Francisco 49ers 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195209280sfo.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 2: at Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=0 |V2=14 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host=Los Angeles\n|H1=0|H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 3\n|Location=[[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=42,743\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Friday, October 3, 1952, the Lions defeated the defending NFL champion [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], 17\u201314, at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. [[Bobby Layne]] threw two touchdown passes to [[Cloyce Box]], the first set up by a [[Les Bingaman]] interception. The Lions led, 14\u20130, but the Rams scored later in the second quarter on a 20-yard run. [[Doak Walker]] kicked a 13-yard field goal in the third quarter that ended up providing the deciding margin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne Hits Box With 2 TD Passes: Lions Lead Rams in Final Period, 17-14|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=13, 14|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225856/lions_lead_rams_in_final_period/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 17 at Los Angeles Rams 14|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210030ram.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 3: San Francisco===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''San Francisco'''\n|V1=0 |V2=14 |V3=7 |V4=7\n|Host=Detroit\n|H1=0|H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=0\n|Date=October 12\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=56,822\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 12, 1952, the Lions lost, 28-0 for the fifth consecutive time to the San Francisco 49ers.  The Lions did not convert a first down in the first half, totaled only 114 yards of offense in the game, and were shut out for the first time since October 1948.  The game was played at Briggs Stadium in front of the largest home crowd (56,822) in Lions history to that point. Bob Latshaw in the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' called it \"as inept an exhibition as has ever been seen in Briggs Stadium\", as the 49ers \"smother[ed] any semblance of a Detroit offense.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions At Worst for Best Crowd in Detroit History: 56,822 See 49ers Stage 28-0 Rout; Home Forces Held to 4 First Downs|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 13, 1952|pages=25, 27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226085/lions_at_worst_for_best_crowd_in/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=San Francisco 49ers 28 at Detroit Lions 0|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210120det.htm}}</ref>  Having been billed as a championship contender in the preseason, the Lions had a 1-2 record after three regular season games.\n\n===Week 4: Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Los Angeles\n|V1=6 |V2=7 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=0|H2=7 |H3=14 |H4=3\n|Date=October 19\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=40,152\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 19, 1952, the Lions defeated the Los Angeles Rams, 24-16, in front of a crowd of 40,152 at Briggs Stadium. After the Lions' poor performance the prior week against the 49ers, the Detroit crowd booed the Lions as they came onto the field. The boos continued as the Rams took a 13-0 lead in the second quarter.  From that point forward, the Lions outscored the Rams, 24 to 3. The comeback began with a 64-yard touchdown pass from [[Bobby Layne]] to [[Cloyce Box]].  The Lions scored two more touchdowns in the third quarter on a 29-yard interception return by [[LaVern Torgeson]] and a 10-yard touchdown pass from [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] to Cloyce Box. [[Pat Harder]] added a field goal in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Spot Rams 13-0 Lead, Roar to 24-16 Victory: Turn Jeers of 40,152 to Cheers; Box Scores 2 TDs as Harder Lifts Club|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 20, 1952|page=33|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226210/lions_spot_rams_130_lead_roar_to/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Rams 16 at Detroit Lions 24|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210190det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 5: at Green Bay===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=14 |V2=14 |V3=14 |V4=10\n|Host=Green Bay\n|H1= 7|H2=3 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 26\n|Location=[[City Stadium (Green Bay)|City Stadium]], [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=24,656\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 26, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], 52\u201317, before a crowd of 24,656 at [[City Stadium (Green Bay)|City Stadium]] in Green Bay. The 52 points scored by the Lions tied the franchise's all-time, single-game scoring record. [[Bobby Layne]] threw three touchdown passes, and [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] rushed for two touchdowns. [[Jug Girard]] caught two touchdown passes and gained 130 yards, 69 receiving and 61 rushing.  The Lions also scored on a 46-yard interception return by [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] and a 65-yard punt return by [[Jack Christiansen]].  The defense held the Packers to 53 rushing yards, recovered four fumbles, and intercepted five passes. [[Pat Harder]] scored nine points on a 16-yard field goal and six extra points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Packers Just What Doctor Ordered for Lions, 52 to 17: Layne Goes by Air for 3 Touchdowns; Defensive Unit Has Hand in 4 Scores|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=33, 35|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225044/packers_just_what_doctor_ordered_for/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 52 at Green Bay Packers 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195210260gnb.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 6: Cleveland===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cleveland\n|V1=3 |V2=0 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=0|H2=10 |H3=0 |H4=7\n|Date=November 2\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=56,029\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 2, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], 17-6, in front of a crowd of 56,029 at Briggs Stadium.  The game was the first meeting between the Lions and the Browns, the latter having joined the NFL in 1950.  On defense, the Lions forced four turnovers, including three interceptions, and held the Browns to two [[Lou Groza]] field goals.  On offense, [[Bobby Layne]] threw two touchdown passes to [[Leon Hart]]. Hart, playing on his 24th birthday, caught eight passes for 109 yards.  [[Pat Harder]] also kicked a 43-yard field goal. Defensive end [[Jim Doran]] at one point sacked Cleveland quarterback [[Otto Graham]] on consecutive plays for losses totaling 36 yards.  The Lions intercepted three passes and held the Browns to 12 rushing yards in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|title=56,029 See Leon Tally 2: Lions Beat Browns, 17-6, with Layne-Hart Punch|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 3, 1952|pages=33, 35|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226355/lions_beat_browns_176/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland Browns 6 at Detroit Lions 17|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211020det.htm}}</ref><ref name=haslubr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YmNQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fw8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4556%2C2617521 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Hart ace as Lions upset Browns, 17-6 |date=November 3, 1952 |page=4, part 2 }}</ref>\n\n===Week 7: at Pittsburgh===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=3 |V2=7 |V3=7 |V4=14\n|Host=Pittsburgh\n|H1=0|H2=0 |H3=6 |H4=0\n|Date=November 9\n|Location=[[Forbes Field]], [[Pittsburgh]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=26,170\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 9, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], 31\u20136, before a crowd of 26,170 at [[Forbes Field]] in Pittsburgh. Usually a pass-oriented offense, the Lions adopted a different approach against the Steelers, rushing for a season-high 321 yards. [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] rushed for 107 yards on 20 carries, and [[Jug Girard]] contributed 71 yards and two touchdowns on six carries. [[Bobby Layne]] completed only four of 17 passes  for 70 yards, 46 of which came on a touchdown pass to [[Cloyce Box]] in the third quarter.  On defense, the Lions held the Steelers to minus three yards rushing and intercepted two passes.  Defensive halfback [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] recovered a fumbled lateral that set up a field goal in the first quarter and returned an interception 90 yards late in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Win, Tie 49ers for Lead: Pittsburgh Ground to Bits, 31-6; Hunchy, Girard Pace Vicious Rushing Race|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 10, 1952|pages=33, 34|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226768/pittsburgh_ground_to_bits_316/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 31 at Pittsburgh Steelers 6|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211090pit.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 8: Dallas===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Dallas\n|V1=0 |V2=0 |V3=13 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1=10 |H2=19 |H3=0 |H4=14\n|Date=November 16\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=33,304\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 16, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]], 43\u201313, before a crowd of 33,304 at Briggs Stadium. The loss was the eighth straight for the Texans.  In the first half, the Lions took a 29-0 lead on two [[Pat Harder]] field goals, a 58-yard punt return by [[Yale Lary]], an eight-yard run by [[Bobby Layne]], a 55-yard touchdown pass from Layne to [[Cloyce Box]], and a safety when defensive end [[Sonny Gandee]] tackled Pittsburgh quarterback [[Frank Tripucka]] in the end zone. In the fourth quarter, Harder kicked his third field goal, and fullback [[Ollie Cline]] scored on a two-yard run.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Hand Dallas 8th Loss, 43-13: Stay Tied with 49ers for League Lead|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|page=33|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226836/lions_hand_dallas_8th_loss/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dallas Texans 13 at Detroit Lions 43|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211160det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 9: at Chicago===\n\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Detroit\n|V1=3 |V2=13 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host='''Chicago'''\n|H1=10|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=7\n|Date=November 23\n|Location=[[Wrigley Field]], [[Chicago]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=37,508\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 23, 1952, the Lions lost to the [[1952 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], 24\u201323, before a crowd of 37,508 at [[Wrigley Field]] in [[Chicago]]. [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] scored two rushing touchdowns, and [[Pat Harder]] also kicked a 31-yard field goal for the Lions.  The Lions led, 16\u201310, at halftime, but the Bears took the lead in the third quarter on a 59-yard touchdown pass from [[George Blanda]] to [[Billy Stone (American football)|Billy Stone]].  The Lions retook the lead, 23\u201317, when [[Jack Christiansen]] returned a punt 79 yards for a touchdown in the fourth quarter.  With nine seconds left in the game, Blanda threw a two-yard touchdown pass to [[Ed Sprinkle]] for the winning score.<ref>{{cite news|title=9 Seconds Left \u2013 Bears Shade Lions, 24 to 23: Long Drive Offsets 79-Yard TD Run by Christiansen|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 24, 1952|page=32|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4226932/bears_shade_lions/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 23 at Chicago Bears 24|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211230chi.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 10: Green Bay===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Green Bay\n|V1=3 |V2=14 |V3=7 |V4=0\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 3|H2=21 |H3=7 |H4=17\n|Date=November 27\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=39,101\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Thanksgiving Day, November 27, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], 48\u201324, before a crowd of 39,101 at Briggs Stadium. The Lions scored 100 points in two games against the Packers during the 1952 season. In the Thanksgiving game, the Lions scored on five touchdown passes \u2013 three thrown by [[Bobby Layne]] and three caught by [[Cloyce Box]]. Layne accounted for over 300 yards of total offense \u2013 63 yards on 13 rushing carries and 249 yards on 16 of 30 passing. Box caught a total of nine passes for 155 yards. [[Pat Harder]] scored 17 points on a touchdown run, two field goals, and five extra points.  On defense, the Lions forced eight turnovers, including six fumble recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=On Turkey Day, Lions Cook Packers' Goose, 48-24: 39,101 See Detroit Get 1st Place|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 27, 1952|pages=43, 46|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4225360/on_turkey_day_lions_cook_packers_goose/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Green Bay Packers 24 at Detroit Lions 48|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195211270det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 11: Chicago===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Chicago\n|V1=7 |V2=7 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 14|H2=7 |H3=10 |H4=14\n|Date=December 7\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=50,410\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 7, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], 45\u201321, before a crowd of 50,410 at [[Briggs Stadium]]. The game was the Lions' first victory over the Bears in Detroit since 1945. [[Bobby Layne]] and [[Cloyce Box]] connected for three touchdown passes in the first half: for 29 and 28 yards in the first quarter and for 25 yards in the second quarter. Layne also threw an 11-yard pass to [[Jim Doran]] in the third quarter. In all, Layne completed 22 of 35 passes for 296 yards. Detroit's defense held the Bears to 37 rushing yards and 171 passing yards and intercepted six Chicago passes.  Defensive back [[Jack Christiansen]] also played at running back, rushing for 54 yards and a touchdown on six carries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Brush Bears Aside, 45-21: Layne Hits Box for 3 Touchdows|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 8, 1952|page=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4224039/lions_brush_bears_aside/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago Bears 21 at Detroit Lions 45|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212070det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Week 12: Dallas===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Dallas\n|V1=0 |V2=0 |V3=0 |V4=6\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 0|H2=14 |H3=10 |H4=17\n|Date=December 13\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=12,252\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Saturday, December 13, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Dallas Texans season|Dallas Texans]], 41\u20136, before a small crowd of 12,252 at [[Briggs Stadium]].  With the win and the Rams' victory the following day, the Lions and Rams became co-champions of the NFL's National Conference. The game had originally been scheduled for December 14 in Dallas, but the NFL assumed control of the Texans one month earlier, and NFL commissioner [[Bert Bell]] decided that the Texans would play their remaining games \"on the road.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bmNQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fw8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2159%2C5094346 |newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|Milwaukee Sentinel]] |agency=Associated Press |title=NFL takes over Dallas Texans |date=November 15, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/11/15/archives/national-football-league-takes-franchise-back-from-dallas-club.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |agency=Associated Press |title=National Football League takes franchise back from Dallas club |date=November 14, 1952 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Bobby Layne]] led the Lions to a 14\u20130 lead in the first half on touchdown passes of 18 yards (a [[Flea flicker (American football)|flea flicker]] with Layne passing to [[Cloyce Box]] who immediately lateraled the ball to [[Pat Harder]]) and 77 yards to [[Cloyce Box]]. Layne was injured (strained knee ligament) shortly before halftime and did not return to the game. [[Jim Hardy]] took over at quarterback and led the Lions to 27 points in the second half, including two touchdown passes to Box of 40 and 41 yards.  [[Jack Christiansen]] also ran 65 yards for a touchdown in the fourth quarter, the Lions' longest rushing play of the season.  Layne completed 10 of 20 passes for 167 yards, and Hardy completed nine of 15 passes for 147 yards.  Box caught a total of seven passes for 202 yards and three touchdowns, setting a new Lions' team record with 15 touchdown receptions in a season.  Harder scored 17 points in the game on a touchdown, two field goals, and five extra points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Layne Hurt, but Lions Win Share of Title: 41\u20136 Rout Completed by Hardy; Bobby's Knee Hurt; Box Sets TD Mark|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 14, 1952|page=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4222734/layne_hurt_but_lions_win/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dallas Texans 6 at Detroit Lions 41|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212130det.htm}}</ref>\n\n===Playoff game \u2013 Los Angeles===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Los Angeles\n|V1=0 |V2=7 |V3=0 |V4=14\n|Host='''Detroit'''\n|H1= 7|H2=7 |H3=10 |H4=7\n|Date=December 21\n|Location=[[Briggs Stadium]], [[Detroit]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=47,645\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 21, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], 31\u201321, in a playoff game to decide who would advance to the NFL Championship Game.  The Lions had beaten the Rams twice in the regular season and were a 1\u00bd-point favorite in the playoff.<ref name=flirdu>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sCkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tA8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3716%2C6056106 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Favor Lions by 1\u00bd points in Ram duel |date=December 21, 1952 |page=3B }}</ref>  The playoff game was played in heavy fog and rain at [[Briggs Stadium]] before a crowd of 47,645. [[Pat Harder]] led both teams with 72 rushing yards on eight carries and scored 19 points on two touchdown runs in the first half, a 43-yard field goal in the third quarter, and four extra points.  The Rams double-teamed and sometimes triple-teamed [[Cloyce Box]], which opened the running game and allowed [[Leon Hart]] to have one of his best receiving days. Hart scored in the third quarter on a 24-yard pass from [[Doak Walker]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Beat Rams, 31\u201321, to Gain NFL Title Playoff: 'Old Pros' Make Good in Clutch; Harder Scores 19; Late LA Rally Halted|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 22, 1952|pages=33, 34|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4222879/lions_beat_rams/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Rams 21 at Detroit Lions 31|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212210det.htm}}</ref><ref name=hchup19>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2EUxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7240%2C91924 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Harder chalks up 19 points in Lions' 31-21 playoff triumph over Rams |date=December 22, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref name=hlltworms>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hHxIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4WoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4695%2C6214058 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |agency=Associated Press |title=Harder leads Lions to 31-21 win over Rams |date=December 22, 1952 |page=22}}</ref>\n\n===NFL Championship Game===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor='''Detroit'''\n|V1=0 |V2=7 |V3=7 |V4=3\n|Host=Cleveland\n|H1= 0|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=December 28\n|Location=[[Cleveland Stadium|Memorial Stadium]], [[Cleveland]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=50,934\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn December 28, 1952, the Lions defeated the [[1952 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], 17\u20137, in the [[1952 NFL Championship Game]] at [[Cleveland Stadium|Memorial Stadium]] in [[Cleveland]]. The Lions had defeated the Browns in both a preseason game and in a regular season game and were favored by 3\u00bd points.<ref name=lhaft>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3kUxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1843%2C1153999 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Lions, hot after 1st title, favored by 3\u00bd points |date=December 28, 1952 |page=1B }}</ref>\n\n[[Bobby Layne]] rushed for a touchdown in the second quarter, and the Lions led, 7\u20130, at halftime. In the third quarter, [[Doak Walker]] ran 67 yards for a touchdown to extend the Lions' lead to 14 points. Walker's touchdown in the championship game was his first of the 1952 season.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote: \"The Doaker was the Walker of old as he twisted and turned, eluded tackler after tackler and ran 67 yards for the Lions' second touchdown.\"<ref name=DFPC/>  The Browns narrowed the lead to 14\u20137 on a seven-yard touchdown run by [[Chick Jagade]] in the third quarter. [[Pat Harder]] added a 36-yard field goal in the fourth quarter. The Browns' outgained the Lions 384 yards to 258 and had 22 first downs to 10 for Detroit.  The Lions' defense mounted four goal-line stands against the Browns' offense led by [[Otto Graham]], and [[Lou Groza]] missed three field goal attempts.<ref name=DFPC>{{cite news|title=Lions Beat Browns, 17\u20137, Win NFL Title: 50,934 See Defense Turn Tide: Detroit Rides Two Mistakes To Victory|author=Bob Latshaw|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 29, 1952|pages=19, 20|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4223368/lions_beat_browns/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit Lions 17 at Cleveland Browns 7|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/195212280cle.htm}}</ref><ref name=ltrpbr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=30UxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RhAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7077%2C1944826 |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Lions trip Browns, 17-7, for NFL crown |date=December 29, 1952 |page=2, part 2 }}</ref><ref name=ldfppgjsl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4UUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kGoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6140%2C1346058 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |last=Sell |first=Jack |title=Lions defeat Browns for NFL title, 17-7 |date=December 29, 1952 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards, honors and league leaders==\n\n===Team awards===\nAt the end of the regular season, the Lions players selected defensive end [[Jim Doran]] as the team's most valuable player.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Honor End Jim Doran|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=December 25, 1952|page=13|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4221586/lions_honor_end_jim_doran/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===All-NFL honors===\n\nThe following six Lions players won All-NFL honors from the [[Associated Press]] (AP), [[United Press International]] (UPI) and/or the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'':\n\n* [[Cloyce Box]] (1st team [[Associated Press]] [AP])\n* [[Lou Creekmur]] (1st team AP, [[United Press]] [UP], and ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' [DN])\n* [[Pat Harder]] (2nd team, AP)\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]] (1st team DN, 2nd team AP/UP)\n* [[Bobby Layne]] (1st team AP, 2nd team DN)\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]] (1st team UP and DN, 2nd team AP)\n\n===Pro Bowl===\nThe following seven Lions players were selected to play in the [[1953 Pro Bowl]]:<ref>{{cite web|title=1952 Pro Bowlers|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/probowl.htm}}</ref>\n* [[Cloyce Box]]\n* [[Lou Creekmur]]\n* [[Don Doll]]\n* [[Pat Harder]]\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]]\n* [[Bobby Layne]]\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]]\n\n===NFL leaders===\nSeveral Lions players were also among the NFL leaders in various statistical categories, including the following:<ref>{{cite web|title=1952 NFL Leaders and Leaderboards|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=February 4, 2016|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/leaders.htm}}</ref>\n\n* [[Cloyce Box]]\n:: 15 touchdowns (1st)\n:: 15 receiving touchdowns (1st)\n:: 90 points scored (2nd)\n:: 924 receiving yards (4th)\n:: 22.0 yards per reception (4th)\n:: 77.0 receiving yards per game (4th)\n:: 924 yards from scrimmage (6th)\n:: 42 receptions (9th)\n\n* [[Jack Christiansen]]\n:: 21.5 yards per punt return (1st)\n:: 2 punt returns for touchdown (T-1st)\n:: 79-yard punt return (4th)\n:: 731 punt and kick return yards (4th)\n:: 65-yard rush (7th)\n:: 322 punt return yards (5th)\n:: 25.6 yards per kick return (6th)\n:: 409 kick return yards (10th)\n\n* [[Blaine Earon]]\n:: 5 fumbles recovered (T-2nd)\n\n* [[Pat Harder]]\n:: 85 points scored (4th)\n:: 34 extra points made (2nd)\n:: 11 field goals made (T-2nd)\n:: 47.826 field goal percentage (6th)\n\n* [[Bob Hoernschemeyer]]\n:: 457 rushing yards (5th)\n:: 4.3 yards per rushing attempt (5th)\n:: 45.7 rushing yards per game (6th)\n\n* [[Yale Lary]]\n:: 25.3 yards per kick return (T-7th)\n:: 182 punt return yards (8th)\n:: 11.4 yards per punt return (8th)\n:: 53-yard interception return (8th)\n:: 58-yard punt return (9th)\n\n* [[Bobby Layne]]\n:: 2,410 yards total offense (2nd)\n:: 20 passes intercepted (2nd)\n:: 139 passes completed (3rd)\n:: 1,999 passing yards (3rd)\n:: 19 passing touchdowns (3rd)\n:: 166.6 passing yards per game (3rd)\n:: 4.4 yards per rushing attempt (4th)\n:: 48.4 pass completion percentage (7th)\n:: 411 rushing yards (7th)\n\n* [[Bob Smith (defensive back, born 1925)|Bob Smith]]\n:: 44.7 yards per punt (2nd)\n:: 90-yard interception return (2nd)\n:: 9 interceptions (3rd)\n:: 184 interception return yards (3rd)\n:: 2,729 punting yards (6th)\n\n===Pro Football Hall of Fame===\nFive members of the team were later inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame. They are:\n* [[Bobby Layne]] (inducted 1967)\n* [[Jack Christiansen]] (inducted 1970)\n* [[Yale Lary]] (inducted 1979)\n* [[Doak Walker]] (inducted 1986)\n* [[Lou Creekmur]] (inducted 1996)\n* [[Dick Stanfel]] (inducted 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/1952.htm?redir Detroit Lions on Pro Football Reference]\n*[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x26rm0z_1952-nfl-championship-lions-vs-browns_sport Video: 1952 NFL Championship Lions vs Browns]\n\n{{Detroit Lions seasons}} \n{{1952 Detroit Lions}}\n{{Detroit Lions}}\n{{1952 NFL season by team}}\n\n[[Category:1952 National Football League season by team|Detroit Lions]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions seasons]]\n[[Category:National Football League championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1952 in sports in Michigan|Detroit Lions]]\n", "name_user": "74.37.88.9", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePro Bowl)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1952_Detroit_Lions_season"}
{"title_page": "Vilayet Printing House (Sarajevo)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox publisher\n| name         = Sopron's Printing House<br/>{{small|(April\u2013October 1866)}}<br/>Vilayet Printing House<br/>{{small|(October 1866 \u2013 August 1878)}}\n| image        = [[File:Bosanski vjestnik nameplate.png|250px]]\n| caption      = Nameplate of ''Bosanski vjestnik'', the first newspaper to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| parent       = \n| status       = Defunct (1878)\n| traded_as    =\n| predecessor  =\n| founded      = {{Start date|1866}}\n| founder      = [[Ignjat Sopron]]\n| successor    = \n| country      = [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| headquarters = [[Sarajevo]]\n| distribution = [[Vilayet of Bosnia]]\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Newspapers, books\n| topics       = Politics, law, education, culture, religion\n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = Ignjat Sopron (April\u2013October 1866); Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia (October 1866 \u2013 August 1878)\n| numemployees =\n| url          = \n}}\nThe '''Vilayet Printing House''' ({{lang-sh|\u0412\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430, Vilajetska \u0161tamparija}}), originally named '''Sopron's Printing House''' (\u0421\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u045a\u0430, ''Sopronova pe\u010datnja''), was the official [[printing house]] of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Vilayet of Bosnia]] from April 1866 until the [[Austro-Hungarian campaign in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1878|occupation of the province]] by [[Austria-Hungary]] in August 1878. It was the second printing house that operated in the territory of present-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], founded in [[Sarajevo]] almost 350 years after the [[Gora\u017ede printing house]] ceased its activity. Its founder was [[Ignjat Sopron]], a publisher and printer from [[Zemun]], who sold the establishment to the Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia in October 1866. Its foundation happened in the context of modernising and Europeanising [[Tanzimat]] reforms in the Ottoman Empire. Its principal aim was to issue an official gazette of the ''vilayet'' and publish textbooks for the elementary schools of Bosnian Serbs and Croats, thus stopping their import from the [[Principality of Serbia]] and the [[Austrian Empire]].\n\nThe first newspaper to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina was ''Bosanski vjestnik'', a political-informative and educational weekly edited by Sopron and printed in [[Serbian Cyrillic alphabet|Serbian Cyrillic]]. It had a pro-Serb inclination, though it generally promoted a unitary Bosnian nation, in accordance with the Ottoman policy in the province. The official gazette, the weekly ''Bosna'', was primarily concerned with publishing and explaining laws, orders, and proclamations. Another weekly issued by the printing house was ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'', which fiercely defended the Ottoman regime and polemicised with Serbian and Austrian newspapers that criticised it. ''Bosna'' and ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' were bilingual, printed half in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] and half in Serbo-Croatian in the Cyrillic script. The printing house produced a number of elementary school textbooks, including the second [[Serbian language|Serbian]] [[alphabet book]] using the reformed Serbian Cyrillic, following [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]]'s book published in Vienna in 1827. Other books include a collection of Bosnian Serb lyric folk poetry, an Ottoman Turkish grammar, and several Jewish religious books. The first printed exemplar of Bosnian [[Aljamiado]] literature was also published by the Vilayet Printing House. It produced around 50 books and booklets altogether, most of them being concerned with various Ottoman laws and legislation.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Gora\u017ede printing house]] was one of the earliest among the [[Serbs]] and the first in the territory of present-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It was founded by [[Bo\u017eidar Ljubavi\u0107]] near the town of [[Gora\u017ede]] in 1519, in the early period of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule over the region. It produced three Orthodox religious books, including the [[Gora\u017ede Psalter]], with its last book printed in 1523. The next printing house would not be opened in Bosnia and Herzegovina until the second half of the 19th century.{{sfn|Lovrenovi\u0107|2001|pp=123\u201324}}\n\nIn the first half of the 19th century, the Ottoman Empire was swept by a wave of reforms meant to centralise and Europeanise the government of the state. Bosnian Muslim feudal lords rejected the reforms and repeatedly revolted against the [[Ottoman Sultan|Sultan]]. The Ottoman military intervened in the [[Eyalet of Bosnia]] in 1831 and 1850, crushing the local feudal lords, and the set of modernising reforms known as the [[Tanzimat]] began to be implemented in the province. The Christians were underprivileged in the Ottoman Empire, and this was even more so in Bosnia than in the rest of the empire. An improvement in this respect occurred in 1862, when the Bosnian Christians ([[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Orthodox Serbs]] and [[Bosnian Croats|Catholic Croats]]) were granted more rights, including those to open new churches and to run their own schools. This came after several uprisings by the Christians,{{sfn|McCarthy|1996|pp=74\u201378}} especially Serbs, who had the strongest national movement in the province.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=254\u201355}} [[Ivan Franjo Juki\u0107]] and other [[Franciscan Province of Bosna Srebrena|Bosnian Franciscans]] requested the right to establish a printing house in 1847, 1850, 1853, and 1857, but each time their requests were denied by the Ottoman government.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nThe reforms became firmly rooted in Bosnia during the 1860s, when the Ottoman governor (''[[W\u0101li|vali]]'') of the province was Topal Sherif Osman Pasha, though most of the changes proceeded at a slow pace.{{sfn|McCarthy|1996|pp=74\u201378}} According to the recently issued Ottoman constitutional law, each ''[[vilayet]]'' (first-order administrative division) was to have an official printing house and an official gazette.{{sfn|Papi\u0107|1976|p=160}} The Constitutional Law for the [[Vilayet of Bosnia]], published in 1865, promoted the province from the rank of eyalet to that of vilayet, and Article&nbsp;9 of this law stipulated that there be an official printing house in its capital.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} Osman Pasha also had other motivations to establish a printing house. At that time, the press in the [[Principality of Serbia]] and in South Slavic parts of the [[Austrian Empire]] sharply criticised the Ottoman regime in Bosnia. Textbooks imported from Serbia for Serb elementary schools in Bosnia also disseminated nationalist sentiment,{{sfn|Papi\u0107|1976|p=160}} which Osman Pasha saw as anti-Ottoman. In his view, the national movement of the Serbs in Bosnia presented a danger for Ottoman state interests.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} To protect their hold on Bosnia, the Ottomans sought to promote the idea of a unitary Bosnian nation, thus counteracting the particular national identities and political aspirations of Bosnia's Serbs, Croats, and Muslims.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=254\u201355}}{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}}\n\n==History and publications==\n\n===Under Sopron===\n[[File:Topal Sherif Osman Pasha.jpg|thumb|right|Topal Sherif Osman Pasha]]\nShortly after the Constitutional Law for the Vilayet of Bosnia was issued, Osman Pasha invited publishing magnate [[Ignjat Sopron]] to Sarajevo. Sopron was the owner and manager of a publishing and printing house in [[Zemun]] (then part of the Austrian Empire, today one of the municipalities of [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]).{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} An ethnic German, he was born in 1821 in [[Novi Sad]] as Ignaz Karl Soppron.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} Upon his arrival in Sarajevo, Osman Pasha offered him a subsidy to establish and organise a printing house. It was to be headquartered in a building on Sarajevo's ''Dugi sokak'' street that was being rented by the vilayet's government.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=12\u201313}} Sopron soon came to the city bringing with him printing tools and materials, accompanied by a [[Typesetting|typesetter]] from Belgrade, Ilija Tomi\u0107. Tomi\u0107 was in charge of the [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] and [[Latin alphabet|Latin]] letters, and he engaged three graduated students of the Serb secondary school in Sarajevo to be his trainees. Osman Pasha also invited a man named Kadri-effendi from [[Istanbul]] to work as the typesetter for [[Arabic script|Arabic]] letters.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=12\u201313}} The principal aim of the printing house was to issue an official gazette and to publish elementary school textbooks, thus stopping their import from Serbia and Austria.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}\n\n''Sopronova pe\u010datnja'', or Sopron's Printing House, was officially opened on {{OldStyleDate|19&nbsp;April|1866|7&nbsp;April}}.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} The Cyrillic orthography that was used in it was consistently in accordance with the linguistic reform of Serbian philologist [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], which was at that time relatively new and still not universally accepted.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=49}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|p=19}} The first issue of a political-informative and educational weekly newspaper named ''Bosanski vjestnik'' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u0411\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0458\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a}}, \"Bosnian Herald\") appeared on the same day.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} This was the first newspaper ever to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=71}} Sopron made a deal with the vilayet's authorities to publish it independently from the official gazette.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} When Sopron presented the editorial policy of his newspaper to the authorities, he indicated that it would be printed in the Serbian language, much to the Ottomans' displeasure. The authorities subsequently scratched \"Serbian\" and replaced it with \"Bosnian\". Sopron accepted the revision and went along with Osman Pasha's idea of promoting a unitary Bosnian nation.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}} Nevertheless, ''Bosanski vjestnik'' had \"a decidedly Serb orientation\".{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=71}} Sopron did not consider this contradictory, as he apparently identified Bosnian-ness with Serbness. In the newspaper, the language was occasionally referred to as Serbo-Bosnian, while both the Serb and the Croat ethnic designations were expressed.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}}\n\nThe first issue of the official gazette, named ''Bosna'' ([[Ottoman Turkish alphabet|Ottoman Turkish]]: {{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0646\u0647}}; Cyrillic: \u0411\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0430, \"Bosnia\"), appeared on {{OldStyleDate|28&nbsp;May|1866|16&nbsp;May}}, i.e., 13&nbsp;Muharram 1283 [[Anno Hegirae|AH]]. It was a bilingual weekly with half of the pages printed in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] in the Arabic script, and the other half printed in Serbo-Croatian in the Cyrillic script. The text in Serbo-Croatian was a faithful translation of that in Turkish. The gazette was primarily concerned with publishing and explaining laws, orders, and proclamations, but it also provided news from the political, economic, cultural, and social life of the vilayet. It would be issued without interruption for more than twelve years, and for much of that period it was the only newspaper in the Vilayet of Bosnia. It had different editors over time: Mustafa Rifet Imamovi\u0107, Mehmed \u0160akir Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, Salih Biogradlija, Javer Baruh, Nurudin Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, and Kadri-effendi. Most of them were Bosnian Muslims, except Baruh (a Jew) and Kadri-effendi (a Turk). A constant in the gazette was its translator from Turkish, Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107,{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}} a polyglot who had previously worked as a teacher in a Serb elementary school in [[Prijepolje]]. Besides Sopron, Mandi\u0107 was one of the contributors to ''Bosanski vjestnik'', along with Bogoljub Petranovi\u0107 and Salih Sidki Had\u017eihuseinovi\u0107. Petranovi\u0107 was the manager of the Serb secondary school in Sarajevo and the leader of the Serb youth movement in the city, while Had\u017eihuseinovi\u0107 was an official of the [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]].{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} In August 1866, the printing house published its first book, ''Lesson on Man and His Duties'' (''\u041d\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043e \u0447\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443 \u0438 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c \u0434\u0443\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430''), translated from Greek by Georgije Jovanovi\u0107.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}}\n\n===Under the vilayet government===\n[[File:Bukvar (Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107, 1867) 11.png|thumb|Mandi\u0107's alphabet book, page 11]]\nIn October 1866, Sopron sold the establishment to the Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} It was renamed ''Vilajetska pe\u010datnja'', or the Vilayet Printing House, and from March 1867 onwards it bore the name ''Vilajetska \u0161tamparija'' (the same meaning).{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}} Sopron remained the owner and editor of ''Bosanski vjestnik'', and managed to publish 51 issues.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} After a year in Sarajevo, Sopron left the city and returned to Zemun.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} The first director of the printing house was Haim Davi\u010do, a Belgrade Jew, who was offered that position by Osman Pasha.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} Mehmed \u0160akir Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, the editor of ''Bosna'' since early 1868, began publishing ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' at the end of that year. It was a bilingual weekly like ''Bosna'', containing commentaries on current politics and articles on various social issues, most of which was written by Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107. He fiercely defended the Ottoman regime in Bosnia, polemicising with newspapers from Serbia and Austria which criticised it.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} In May 1869, when Osman Pasha ceased to be the governor of the Vilayet of Bosnia, Davi\u010do returned to Belgrade. The new governor installed Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107 as the director of the printing house.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107 died of tuberculosis in September 1872;{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} the last issue of ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' had appeared two months earlier.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|p=21}}\n\nKurt\u0107ehaji\u0107's death marked the end of a prosperous period for the Vilayet Printing House. Its subsequent directors were less capable, and the establishment's condition began to deteriorate. In 1877, the last Ottoman governor of Bosnia installed Kadri-effendi as director, and he significantly improved the condition of the printing house. [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] troops entered Sarajevo on 19 August 1878, marking the start of 40 years of Austro-Hungarian occupation. Four days later, General [[Josip Filipovi\u0107]], the Austro-Hungarian commander in Sarajevo, transferred the management of the printing house from Kadri-effendi to an Austrian official. This spelled the end of the Vilayet Printing House, which was renamed ''Zemaljska \u0161tamparija'' (''National Printing Press''), and continued its work as the official printing house of the [[Condominium of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} The last, 636th, issue of ''Bosna'' appeared shortly before the end of Ottoman rule over Bosnia, on {{OldStyleDate|30&nbsp;July|1878|18&nbsp;July}}.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}}\n\nApart from the newspapers ''Bosanski vjestnik'', ''Bosna'', and ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'', the Vilayet Printing House published around fifty books and booklets in Serbo-Croatian, Ottoman Turkish, and Hebrew. While most of these publications were concerned with various Ottoman laws and legislation, the printing house also published a number of textbooks.{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}} The textbooks for Serb elementary schools in the ''vilayet'' were prepared by Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107 on the basis of those that were used in Serbia. These include an [[alphabet book]] (''\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440''), a short Biblical history (''\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430''), a [[basal reader]] (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430''), and the ''First Knowledges'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u045a\u0430''); they were published in 1867 and 1868.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=44\u201346}} Mandi\u0107's alphabet book, the printing house's first textbook, was the second Serbian alphabet book using the reformed Serbian Cyrillic. ''The First Serbian Alphabet Book'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0411\u0443\u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440''), authored by Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107, had been published in Vienna in 1827.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}} The original plan was to print fifteen textbooks for Serb schools, ranging in subject from grammar, arithmetic, geography and religious teaching, but only four were printed.{{sfn|Sudaru\u0161i\u0107|Panti\u0107|2012|p=543}} Although they were based on the textbooks used in Serbia, the vilayet's authorities made sure that every mention of Serbs and the Serbian language was erased from them.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=252\u201353}}\n\nBogoljub Petranovi\u0107 collected Bosnian Serb lyric folk poems and published them in 1867 in a separate book (''\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0458\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0411\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0435 (\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435)'').{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}} ''The First Bosnian-Serb Calendar for the Common Year 1869'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443 1869''), consisting of 58 pages, was edited by Jovan R. D\u017eini\u0107.{{sfn|Sudaru\u0161i\u0107|Panti\u0107|2012|p=548}} In Serbian tradition, calendars contained more than just calendarical data and were also popular literary and educational almanacs. D\u017eini\u0107's calendar had more of an educational, rather than literary, character.{{sfn|\u0106orovi\u0107|1924|pp=228\u201329}} It also included a collection of advice that was traditionally presented to [[journeyman|journeymen]] during the ''testir'' ceremony of the [[guild]] of tailors in Sarajevo, in which a journeyman was promoted to a [[master craftsman]]. This is the only known text of this kind, beside [[Lazar Jovanovi\u0107 (writer)#Sobornik|a manuscript written in 1841]] for the guild of goldsmiths.{{sfn|Milenkovi\u0107|Vasiljev|2002|pp=342\u201343}}\n\nCatholic school textbooks in the vilayet included a geography book (''Kratka zemljopisna po\u010detnica s dodatkom o Bosni'', 1869) by Franjo \u017d. Franjkovi\u0107, an alphabet book with elements of religious education (''Bukvar s napomenkom \u010dlanakah nauka vjere za katoli\u010dku mlade\u017e u Bosni'', 1869), and another geography book (''Po\u010detni zemljopis za katoli\u010dke u\u010dionice u Bosni'', 1871) by the Franciscan [[Grgo Marti\u0107]]. The Catholic [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Mostar|bishop of Mostar]] Pa\u0161kal Buconji\u0107 financed the printing of an Ottoman Turkish grammar in 1871.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}} The Hebrew books included ''Meshek Beti'' ({{lang|he|\u05de\u05e9\u05e7 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9}}) and ''Appe Zutre'' ({{lang|he|\u05d0\u05e4\u05d9 \u05d6\u05d5\u05d8\u05e8\u05d9}}), which list religious observances, respectively, on [[Shabbat]] and [[Passover]], and a small liturgical book titled ''Tikkun Moda'ah''. These were composed around 1875 by the Sarajevo Rabbi Eliezer Papo.{{sfn|Levy|1911|p=31}} The printing house also published the first printed work of Bosnian [[Aljamiado]] literature, the book ''Sehletul-Vusul'', which contained the principal teachings of Islam. It was composed by Omer Humo, the ''[[mufti]]'' of Mostar.{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|35em}}\n*{{Citation| last=Budi\u0161a| first=Dra\u017een| author-link=Dra\u017een Budi\u0161a| title=Po\u010deci tiskarstva u evropskih naroda| trans-title=Beginnings of Printing among European Peoples| year=1984| publisher=Kr\u0161\u0107anska sada\u0161njost| place=Zagreb| language=Croatian| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7jQLAQAAIAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=\u0106orovi\u0107| first=Vladimir| author-link=Vladimir \u0106orovi\u0107| editor=Svetislav Petrovi\u0107| editor-link=| year=1924| title=\u041a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0437\u0430 1924 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443| trans-title=Calendars for the Year 1924| journal=Srpski knji\u017eevni glasnik| volume=11| issue=1| publisher=[[Bogdan Popovi\u0107]]| place=Belgrade| language=Serbian| url=http://scc.digital.bkp.nb.rs/view/P-1010-1924-001&p=235| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Ekme\u010di\u0107| first=Milorad| author-link=Milorad Ekme\u010di\u0107| title=\u0421\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u0408\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435 1790\u20131918| trans-title=Creation of Yugoslavia 1790\u20131918| year=1989| volume=2| publisher=Prosveta| place=Belgrade| language=Serbian| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=em1pAAAAMAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Hoare| first=Marko Attila| author-link=Marko Attila Hoare| title=The History of Bosnia: From the Middle Ages to the Present Day| year=2007| publisher=Saqi Books| place=London| isbn=978-0-86356-953-1| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OWQtAQAAIAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107| first=Hamdija| author-link=Hamdija Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107| title=\u0160tamparije u Bosni za turskog vremena 1529.\u20131878.|trans-title=Printing Houses in Bosnia in Turkish Times 1529\u20131878| editor=\u0110uro K\u00f6rbler| journal=Gra\u0111a za povijest knji\u017eevnosti hrvatske| year=1920| volume=9| publisher=Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts| place=Zagreb| language=Croatian| url=http://dizbi.hazu.hr/?object=view&id=12119| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation|last=Kru\u0161evac| first=Todor| title=Bosanskohercegova\u010dki listovi u XIX veku| trans-title=Bosnian-Herzegovinian Periodicals in the 19th Century| year=1978| publisher=\"Veselin Masle\u0161a\"| place=Sarajevo| language=Serbian| url=http://digital.nub.rs/pdf/bh_listovi/bh_listovi.pdf| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Levy| first=Moritz| title=Die Sephardim in Bosnien: ein Beitrag zur Geschichte der Juden auf der Balkanhalbinsel| trans-title=The Sephardim in Bosnia: a Contribution to the History of Jews in the Balkans| year=1911| language=German|publisher=Daniel A. Kajon| place=Sarajevo| url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hebis:30:1-100508| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Lovrenovi\u0107| first=Ivan| title=Bosnia: A Cultural History| publisher=Saqi Books| place=London| year=2001| isbn=978-0-8147-5179-4| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BH9pAAAAMAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=McCarthy| first=Justin| author-link=Justin McCarthy (American historian)| editor=Mark Pinson| title=The Muslims of Bosnia-Herzegovina: Their Historic Development from the Middle Ages to the Dissolution of Yugoslavia| year=1996| chapter=Ottoman Bosnia, 1800\u20131878| edition=2nd| publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]| place=Cambridge, Massachusetts| isbn=978-0-932885-12-8| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl3TAkJmztYC&pg=PA74| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last    = Milenkovi\u0107| first   = Svetlana| last2   = Vasiljev| first2  = Ljupka| year     = 2002| title    = \u0408\u043e\u0448 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0408\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u0442\u0435\u0448\u0430\u045a\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0459\u0430| trans-title = Another Manuscript Book by Lazar Jovanovi\u0107, Teacher from Te\u0161anj| journal = Arheografski prilozi (M\u00e9langes arch\u00e9ographiques)| volume  = 24| publisher = [[National Library of Serbia]]| place    = Belgrade| language = Serbian| issn = 0351-2819| url = https://www.nb.rs/view_file.php?file_id=760| mode = cs1| ref = harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Papi\u0107| first=Mitar| title=\u0422\u0440\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0459\u0435\u0452\u0430| trans-chapter=One Hundred Years of the Press in Bosnia and Herzegovina| chapter=\u0421\u0442\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0435 \u0443 \u0411\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0438 \u0438 X\u0435\u0440\u0446\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438| year=1976| publisher=Svjetlost| place=Sarajevo| language=Serbian| url=http://digital.nub.rs/pdf/tragom/tragom.pdf#page=160| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last1=Sudaru\u0161i\u0107| first1=Radoslavka| last2=Panti\u0107| first2=Vlastimir| editor=Bojana Dimitrijevi\u0107| chapter=\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u0443 \u0411\u0438\u0425 \u043e\u0434 1800. \u0434\u043e 1878. \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435| trans-chapter=Serbian Printed Book in Bosnia and Herzegovina from 1800 to 1878| title=\u0424\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0438 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442| year=2012| publisher=Faculty of Philosophy, [[University of Ni\u0161]]| place=Ni\u0161| language=Serbian| isbn=978-86-7379-263-7| url=http://www.filfak.ni.ac.rs/izdavastvo/zbornici/2012/filologija-i-univerzitet.html| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Textbooks for Serb elementary schools in the Vilayet of Bosnia:\n**[http://digital.bms.rs/ebiblioteka/publications/view/1067 \u0411\u0443\u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c], alphabet book (1867)\n**[http://digital.nub.rs/pdf/svestena/svestena.pdf \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c], short Biblical history (1868)\n**[http://www.bgs.ba/eknjige/images/stories/pdf/Prva_citanka_za_osnovne_skole_u_vilajetu_bosanskom.pdf \u041f\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c], basal reader (1868)\n*[http://digitalna.nb.rs/wb/NBS/casopisi_pretrazivi_po_datumu/bosanska_vila/1890/11/b021-22#page/17/mode/1up \u0421\u0430\u0432\u0458\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0430\u0458\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0443 \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0443], part of the ''First Bosnian-Serb Calendar for the Common Year 1869'' (reprinted in 1890)\n\n{{coord|43.8573|N|18.4334|E|type:landmark_region:BA-09|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:History of printing]]\n[[Category:Ottoman period in the history of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Serbian culture]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:History of the Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox publisher\n| name         = Sopron's Printing House<br/>{{small|(April\u2013October 1866)}}<br/>Vilayet Printing House<br/>{{small|(October 1866 \u2013 August 1878)}}\n| image        = [[File:Bosanski vjestnik nameplate.png|250px]]\n| caption      = Nameplate of ''Bosanski vjestnik'', the first newspaper to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| parent       = \n| status       = Defunct (1878)\n| traded_as    =\n| predecessor  =\n| founded      = {{Start date|1866}}\n| founder      = [[Ignjat Sopron]]\n| successor    = \n| country      = [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| headquarters = [[Sarajevo]]\n| distribution = [[Vilayet of Bosnia]]\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Newspapers, books\n| topics       = Politics, law, education, culture, religion\n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = Ignjat Sopron (April\u2013October 1866); Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia (October 1866 \u2013 August 1878)\n| numemployees =\n| url          = \n}}\nThe '''Vilayet Printing House''' ({{lang-sh|\u0412\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430, Vilajetska \u0161tamparija}}), originally named '''Sopron's Printing House''' (\u0421\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u045a\u0430, ''Sopronova pe\u010datnja''), was the official [[printing house]] of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Vilayet of Bosnia]] from April 1866 until the [[Austro-Hungarian campaign in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1878|occupation of the province]] by [[Austria-Hungary]] in August 1878. It was the second printing house that operated in the territory of present-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], founded in [[Sarajevo]] almost 350 years after the [[Gora\u017ede printing house]] ceased its activity. Its founder was [[Ignjat Sopron]], a publisher and printer from [[Zemun]], who sold the establishment to the Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia in October 1866. Its foundation happened in the context of modernising and Europeanising [[Tanzimat]] reforms in the Ottoman Empire. Its principal aim was to issue an official gazette of the ''vilayet'' and publish textbooks for the elementary schools of Bosnian Serbs and Croats, thus stopping their import from the [[Principality of Serbia]] and the [[Austrian Empire]].\n\nThe first newspaper to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina was ''Bosanski vjestnik'', a political-informative and educational weekly edited by Sopron and printed in [[Serbian Cyrillic alphabet|Serbian Cyrillic]]. It had a pro-Serb inclination, though it generally promoted a unitary Bosnian nation, in accordance with the Ottoman policy in the province. The official gazette, the weekly ''Bosna'', was primarily concerned with publishing and explaining laws, orders, and proclamations. Another weekly issued by the printing house was ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'', which fiercely defended the Ottoman regime and polemicised with Serbian and Austrian newspapers that criticised it. ''Bosna'' and ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' were bilingual, printed half in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] and half in Serbo-Croatian in the Cyrillic script. The printing house produced a number of elementary school textbooks, including the second [[Serbian language|Serbian]] [[alphabet book]] using the reformed Serbian Cyrillic, following [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]]'s book published in Vienna in 1827. Other books include a collection of Bosnian Serb lyric folk poetry, an Ottoman Turkish grammar, and several Jewish religious books. The first printed exemplar of Bosnian [[Aljamiado]] literature was also published by the Vilayet Printing House. It produced around 50 books and booklets altogether, most of them being concerned with various Ottoman laws and legislation.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Gora\u017ede printing house]] was one of the earliest among the [[Serbs]] and the first in the territory of present-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It was founded by [[Bo\u017eidar Ljubavi\u0107]] near the town of [[Gora\u017ede]] in 1519, in the early period of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule over the region. It produced three Orthodox religious books, including the [[Gora\u017ede Psalter]], with its last book printed in 1523. The next printing house would not be opened in Bosnia and Herzegovina until the second half of the 19th century.{{sfn|Lovrenovi\u0107|2001|pp=123\u201324}}\n\nIn the first half of the 19th century, the Ottoman Empire was swept by a wave of reforms meant to centralise and Europeanise the government of the state. Bosnian Muslim feudal lords rejected the reforms and repeatedly revolted against the [[Ottoman Sultan|Sultan]]. The Ottoman military intervened in the [[Eyalet of Bosnia]] in 1831 and 1850, crushing the local feudal lords, and the set of modernising reforms known as the [[Tanzimat]] began to be implemented in the province. The Christians were underprivileged in the Ottoman Empire, and this was even more so in Bosnia than in the rest of the empire. An improvement in this respect occurred in 1862, when the Bosnian Christians ([[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Orthodox Serbs]] and [[Bosnian Croats|Catholic Croats]]) were granted more rights, including those to open new churches and to run their own schools. This came after several uprisings by the Christians,{{sfn|McCarthy|1996|pp=74\u201378}} especially Serbs, who had the strongest national movement in the province.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=254\u201355}} [[Ivan Franjo Juki\u0107]] and other [[Franciscan Province of Bosna Srebrena|Bosnian Franciscans]] requested the right to establish a printing house in 1847, 1850, 1853, and 1857, but each time their requests were denied by the Ottoman government.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nThe reforms became firmly rooted in Bosnia during the 1860s, when the Ottoman governor (''[[W\u0101li|vali]]'') of the province was Topal Sherif Osman Pasha, though most of the changes proceeded at a slow pace.{{sfn|McCarthy|1996|pp=74\u201378}} According to the recently issued Ottoman constitutional law, each ''[[vilayet]]'' (first-order administrative division) was to have an official printing house and an official gazette.{{sfn|Papi\u0107|1976|p=160}} The Constitutional Law for the [[Vilayet of Bosnia]], published in 1865, promoted the province from the rank of eyalet to that of vilayet, and Article&nbsp;9 of this law stipulated that there be an official printing house in its capital.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} Osman Pasha also had other motivations to establish a printing house. At that time, the press in the [[Principality of Serbia]] and in South Slavic parts of the [[Austrian Empire]] sharply criticised the Ottoman regime in Bosnia. Textbooks imported from Serbia for Serb elementary schools in Bosnia also disseminated nationalist sentiment,{{sfn|Papi\u0107|1976|p=160}} which Osman Pasha saw as anti-Ottoman. In his view, the national movement of the Serbs in Bosnia presented a danger for Ottoman state interests.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} To protect their hold on Bosnia, the Ottomans sought to promote the idea of a unitary Bosnian nation, thus counteracting the particular national identities and political aspirations of Bosnia's Serbs, Croats, and Muslims.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=254\u201355}}{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}}\n\n==History and publications==\n\n===Under Sopron===\n[[File:Topal Sherif Osman Pasha.jpg|thumb|right|Topal Sherif Osman Pasha]]\nShortly after the Constitutional Law for the Vilayet of Bosnia was issued, Osman Pasha invited publishing magnate [[Ignjat Sopron]] to Sarajevo. Sopron was the owner and manager of a publishing and printing house in [[Zemun]] (then part of the Austrian Empire, today one of the municipalities of [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]).{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}} An ethnic German, he was born in 1821 in [[Novi Sad]] as Ignaz Karl Soppron.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} Upon his arrival in Sarajevo, Osman Pasha offered him a subsidy to establish and organise a printing house. It was to be headquartered in a building on Sarajevo's ''Dugi sokak'' street that was being rented by the vilayet's government.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=12\u201313}} Sopron soon came to the city bringing with him printing tools and materials, accompanied by a [[Typesetting|typesetter]] from Belgrade, Ilija Tomi\u0107. Tomi\u0107 was in charge of the [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] and [[Latin alphabet|Latin]] letters, and he engaged three graduated students of the Serb secondary school in Sarajevo to be his trainees. Osman Pasha also invited a man named Kadri-effendi from [[Istanbul]] to work as the typesetter for [[Arabic script|Arabic]] letters.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=12\u201313}} The principal aim of the printing house was to issue an official gazette and to publish elementary school textbooks, thus stopping their import from Serbia and Austria.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=11\u201312}}\n\n''Sopronova pe\u010datnja'', or Sopron's Printing House, was officially opened on {{OldStyleDate|19&nbsp;April|1866|7&nbsp;April}}.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} The Cyrillic orthography that was used in it was consistently in accordance with the linguistic reform of Serbian philologist [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], which was at that time relatively new and still not universally accepted.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=49}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|p=19}} The first issue of a political-informative and educational weekly newspaper named ''Bosanski vjestnik'' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u0411\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0458\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a}}, \"Bosnian Herald\") appeared on the same day.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} This was the first newspaper ever to be published in Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=71}} Sopron made a deal with the vilayet's authorities to publish it independently from the official gazette.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} When Sopron presented the editorial policy of his newspaper to the authorities, he indicated that it would be printed in the Serbian language, much to the Ottomans' displeasure. The authorities subsequently scratched \"Serbian\" and replaced it with \"Bosnian\". Sopron accepted the revision and went along with Osman Pasha's idea of promoting a unitary Bosnian nation.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}} Nevertheless, ''Bosanski vjestnik'' had \"a decidedly Serb orientation\".{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=71}} Sopron did not consider this contradictory, as he apparently identified Bosnian-ness with Serbness. In the newspaper, the language was occasionally referred to as Serbo-Bosnian, while both the Serb and the Croat ethnic designations were expressed.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|p=32}}\n\nThe first issue of the official gazette, named ''Bosna'' ([[Ottoman Turkish alphabet|Ottoman Turkish]]: {{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0646\u0647}}; Cyrillic: \u0411\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0430, \"Bosnia\"), appeared on {{OldStyleDate|28&nbsp;May|1866|16&nbsp;May}}, i.e., 13&nbsp;Muharram 1283 [[Anno Hegirae|AH]]. It was a bilingual weekly with half of the pages printed in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] in the Arabic script, and the other half printed in Serbo Croatian in the Cyrillic script. The text in Serbo Croatian was a faithful translation of that in Turkish. The gazette was primarily concerned with publishing and explaining laws, orders, and proclamations, but it also provided news from the political, economic, cultural, and social life of the vilayet. It would be issued without interruption for more than twelve years, and for much of that period it was the only newspaper in the Vilayet of Bosnia. It had different editors over time: Mustafa Rifet Imamovi\u0107, Mehmed \u0160akir Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, Salih Biogradlija, Javer Baruh, Nurudin Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, and Kadri-effendi. Most of them were Bosnian Muslims, except Baruh (a Jew) and Kadri-effendi (a Turk). A constant in the gazette was its translator from Turkish, Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107,{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}} a polyglot who had previously worked as a teacher in a Serb elementary school in [[Prijepolje]]. Besides Sopron, Mandi\u0107 was one of the contributors to ''Bosanski vjestnik'', along with Bogoljub Petranovi\u0107 and Salih Sidki Had\u017eihuseinovi\u0107. Petranovi\u0107 was the manager of the Serb secondary school in Sarajevo and the leader of the Serb youth movement in the city, while Had\u017eihuseinovi\u0107 was an official of the [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]].{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} In August 1866, the printing house published its first book, ''Lesson on Man and His Duties'' (''\u041d\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043e \u0447\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443 \u0438 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c \u0434\u0443\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430''), translated from Greek by Georgije Jovanovi\u0107.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}}\n\n===Under the vilayet government===\n[[File:Bukvar (Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107, 1867) 11.png|thumb|Mandi\u0107's alphabet book, page 11]]\nIn October 1866, Sopron sold the establishment to the Government of the Vilayet of Bosnia.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} It was renamed ''Vilajetska pe\u010datnja'', or the Vilayet Printing House, and from March 1867 onwards it bore the name ''Vilajetska \u0161tamparija'' (the same meaning).{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}} Sopron remained the owner and editor of ''Bosanski vjestnik'', and managed to publish 51 issues.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}} After a year in Sarajevo, Sopron left the city and returned to Zemun.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} The first director of the printing house was Haim Davi\u010do, a Belgrade Jew, who was offered that position by Osman Pasha.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} Mehmed \u0160akir Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107, the editor of ''Bosna'' since early 1868, began publishing ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' at the end of that year. It was a bilingual weekly like ''Bosna'', containing commentaries on current politics and articles on various social issues, most of which was written by Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107. He fiercely defended the Ottoman regime in Bosnia, polemicising with newspapers from Serbia and Austria which criticised it.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} In May 1869, when Osman Pasha ceased to be the governor of the Vilayet of Bosnia, Davi\u010do returned to Belgrade. The new governor installed Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107 as the director of the printing house.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} Kurt\u0107ehaji\u0107 died of tuberculosis in September 1872;{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=50\u201352}} the last issue of ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'' had appeared two months earlier.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|p=21}}\n\nKurt\u0107ehaji\u0107's death marked the end of a prosperous period for the Vilayet Printing House. Its subsequent directors were less capable, and the establishment's condition began to deteriorate. In 1877, the last Ottoman governor of Bosnia installed Kadri-effendi as director, and he significantly improved the condition of the printing house. [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] troops entered Sarajevo on 19 August 1878, marking the start of 40 years of Austro-Hungarian occupation. Four days later, General [[Josip Filipovi\u0107]], the Austro-Hungarian commander in Sarajevo, transferred the management of the printing house from Kadri-effendi to an Austrian official. This spelled the end of the Vilayet Printing House, which was renamed ''Zemaljska \u0161tamparija'' (''National Printing Press''), and continued its work as the official printing house of the [[Condominium of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=16\u201317}} The last, 636th, issue of ''Bosna'' appeared shortly before the end of Ottoman rule over Bosnia, on {{OldStyleDate|30&nbsp;July|1878|18&nbsp;July}}.{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=41\u201342}}\n\nApart from the newspapers ''Bosanski vjestnik'', ''Bosna'', and ''Sarajevski cvjetnik'', the Vilayet Printing House published around fifty books and booklets in Serbo-Croatian, Ottoman Turkish, and Hebrew. While most of these publications were concerned with various Ottoman laws and legislation, the printing house also published a number of textbooks.{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}} The textbooks for Serb elementary schools in the ''vilayet'' were prepared by Milo\u0161 Mandi\u0107 on the basis of those that were used in Serbia. These include an [[alphabet book]] (''\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440''), a short Biblical history (''\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430''), a [[basal reader]] (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430''), and the ''First Knowledges'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u045a\u0430''); they were published in 1867 and 1868.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=44\u201346}} Mandi\u0107's alphabet book, the printing house's first textbook, was the second Serbian alphabet book using the reformed Serbian Cyrillic. ''The First Serbian Alphabet Book'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0411\u0443\u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440''), authored by Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107, had been published in Vienna in 1827.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}}{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}} The original plan was to print fifteen textbooks for Serb schools, ranging in subject from grammar, arithmetic, geography and religious teaching, but only four were printed.{{sfn|Sudaru\u0161i\u0107|Panti\u0107|2012|p=543}} Although they were based on the textbooks used in Serbia, the vilayet's authorities made sure that every mention of Serbs and the Serbian language was erased from them.{{sfn|Ekme\u010di\u0107|1989|pp=252\u201353}}\n\nBogoljub Petranovi\u0107 collected Bosnian Serb lyric folk poems and published them in 1867 in a separate book (''\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0458\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0411\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0435 (\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435)'').{{sfn|Kru\u0161evac|1978|pp=27\u201330}}{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}} ''The First Bosnian-Serb Calendar for the Common Year 1869'' (''\u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443 1869''), consisting of 58 pages, was edited by Jovan R. D\u017eini\u0107.{{sfn|Sudaru\u0161i\u0107|Panti\u0107|2012|p=548}} In Serbian tradition, calendars contained more than just calendarical data and were also popular literary and educational almanacs. D\u017eini\u0107's calendar had more of an educational, rather than literary, character.{{sfn|\u0106orovi\u0107|1924|pp=228\u201329}} It also included a collection of advice that was traditionally presented to [[journeyman|journeymen]] during the ''testir'' ceremony of the [[guild]] of tailors in Sarajevo, in which a journeyman was promoted to a [[master craftsman]]. This is the only known text of this kind, beside [[Lazar Jovanovi\u0107 (writer)#Sobornik|a manuscript written in 1841]] for the guild of goldsmiths.{{sfn|Milenkovi\u0107|Vasiljev|2002|pp=342\u201343}}\n\nCatholic school textbooks in the vilayet included a geography book (''Kratka zemljopisna po\u010detnica s dodatkom o Bosni'', 1869) by Franjo \u017d. Franjkovi\u0107, an alphabet book with elements of religious education (''Bukvar s napomenkom \u010dlanakah nauka vjere za katoli\u010dku mlade\u017e u Bosni'', 1869), and another geography book (''Po\u010detni zemljopis za katoli\u010dke u\u010dionice u Bosni'', 1871) by the Franciscan [[Grgo Marti\u0107]]. The Catholic [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Mostar|bishop of Mostar]] Pa\u0161kal Buconji\u0107 financed the printing of an Ottoman Turkish grammar in 1871.{{sfn|Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107|1920|pp=23\u201328}} The Hebrew books included ''Meshek Beti'' ({{lang|he|\u05de\u05e9\u05e7 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9}}) and ''Appe Zutre'' ({{lang|he|\u05d0\u05e4\u05d9 \u05d6\u05d5\u05d8\u05e8\u05d9}}), which list religious observances, respectively, on [[Shabbat]] and [[Passover]], and a small liturgical book titled ''Tikkun Moda'ah''. These were composed around 1875 by the Sarajevo Rabbi Eliezer Papo.{{sfn|Levy|1911|p=31}} The printing house also published the first printed work of Bosnian [[Aljamiado]] literature, the book ''Sehletul-Vusul'', which contained the principal teachings of Islam. It was composed by Omer Humo, the ''[[mufti]]'' of Mostar.{{sfn|Budi\u0161a|1984|p=176}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|35em}}\n*{{Citation| last=Budi\u0161a| first=Dra\u017een| author-link=Dra\u017een Budi\u0161a| title=Po\u010deci tiskarstva u evropskih naroda| trans-title=Beginnings of Printing among European Peoples| year=1984| publisher=Kr\u0161\u0107anska sada\u0161njost| place=Zagreb| language=Croatian| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7jQLAQAAIAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=\u0106orovi\u0107| first=Vladimir| author-link=Vladimir \u0106orovi\u0107| editor=Svetislav Petrovi\u0107| editor-link=| year=1924| title=\u041a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0437\u0430 1924 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443| trans-title=Calendars for the Year 1924| journal=Srpski knji\u017eevni glasnik| volume=11| issue=1| publisher=[[Bogdan Popovi\u0107]]| place=Belgrade| language=Serbian| url=http://scc.digital.bkp.nb.rs/view/P-1010-1924-001&p=235| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Ekme\u010di\u0107| first=Milorad| author-link=Milorad Ekme\u010di\u0107| title=\u0421\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u0408\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435 1790\u20131918| trans-title=Creation of Yugoslavia 1790\u20131918| year=1989| volume=2| publisher=Prosveta| place=Belgrade| language=Serbian| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=em1pAAAAMAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Hoare| first=Marko Attila| author-link=Marko Attila Hoare| title=The History of Bosnia: From the Middle Ages to the Present Day| year=2007| publisher=Saqi Books| place=London| isbn=978-0-86356-953-1| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OWQtAQAAIAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107| first=Hamdija| author-link=Hamdija Kre\u0161evljakovi\u0107| title=\u0160tamparije u Bosni za turskog vremena 1529.\u20131878.|trans-title=Printing Houses in Bosnia in Turkish Times 1529\u20131878| editor=\u0110uro K\u00f6rbler| journal=Gra\u0111a za povijest knji\u017eevnosti hrvatske| year=1920| volume=9| publisher=Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts| place=Zagreb| language=Croatian| url=http://dizbi.hazu.hr/?object=view&id=12119| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation|last=Kru\u0161evac| first=Todor| title=Bosanskohercegova\u010dki listovi u XIX veku| trans-title=Bosnian-Herzegovinian Periodicals in the 19th Century| year=1978| publisher=\"Veselin Masle\u0161a\"| place=Sarajevo| language=Serbian| url=http://digital.nub.rs/pdf/bh_listovi/bh_listovi.pdf| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Levy| first=Moritz| title=Die Sephardim in Bosnien: ein Beitrag zur Geschichte der Juden auf der Balkanhalbinsel| trans-title=The Sephardim in Bosnia: a Contribution to the History of Jews in the Balkans| year=1911| language=German|publisher=Daniel A. Kajon| place=Sarajevo| url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hebis:30:1-100508| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=Lovrenovi\u0107| first=Ivan| title=Bosnia: A Cultural History| publisher=Saqi Books| place=London| year=2001| isbn=978-0-8147-5179-4| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BH9pAAAAMAAJ| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last=McCarthy| first=Justin| author-link=Justin McCarthy (American historian)| editor=Mark Pinson| title=The Muslims of Bosnia-Herzegovina: Their Historic Development from the Middle Ages to the Dissolution of Yugoslavia| year=1996| chapter=Ottoman Bosnia, 1800\u20131878| edition=2nd| publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]| place=Cambridge, Massachusetts| isbn=978-0-932885-12-8| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl3TAkJmztYC&pg=PA74| mode=cs1| ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation| last    = Milenkovi\u0107| first   = Svetlana| last2   = Vasiljev| first2  = Ljupka| year     = 2002| title    = \u0408\u043e\u0448 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0408\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u